left-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 ''It makes you teary-eyed,'' said the 44-year-old mother of two boys. ''There's so much money in Hartford. Office buildings are going up. The town is flourishing. And I can't find a job, even washing dishes.''  \par \par \uc2 ''Being in the factory the last nine years,'' she continued, ''I never learned any other skills. My kind of skills are out. All the jobs out there, I don't have the skills for.''  \par \par \uc2 Mrs. Hogg's situation and her daily odyssey illustrate the tremendous contradiction in this city. Hartford is booming and going bust simultaneously. And a variety of statistics support each side of the dichotomy.  \par \par \uc2 The Census Bureau recently listed Hartford as the fourth poorest city in the nation, with 25.2 percent of its 136,000 people living below the poverty line - which for a family of four, for example, is an annual income of $7,412. Nearly one in three Hartford residents receives public assistance. Unemployment is 11.7 percent - higher than the national rate and almost twice Connecticut's.  \par \par \uc2 In a study of 153 major cities by the Brookings Institution, Hartford was one of only four cities that had all four of these problems: ''worst distress,'' ''worst decline,'' ''worst disparity'' compared with its suburbs and ''worst divergence'' in growth rate compared with its suburbs.  \par \par \uc2 Yet while other equally and even less poor cities may largely connote images of decay, Hartford exhibits both old money and new growth. The multimillion-dollar insurance industry continues to make Hartford its capital. And a different kind of capital - investment - is behind a building and leasing bonanza in Hartford.  \par \par \uc2 The city expects to open 2.2 million square feet of new commercial space by 1984, including the 16-story 1 Corporate Center and the 38-story City Place, which will become the tallest structure in Connecticut. The construction is not quixotic: Hartford now has a vacancy rate of only 2.9 percent for Class A office space, and City Place is already 75 percent leased.  \par \par \uc2 Yet within the 18-square-mile city, contrast abounds. Across the street from the world headquarters of the Aetna Life and Casualty Company is a soup kitchen. Outside the office of Mayor Thirman Milner is a bin for donations of canned and dried food.  \par \par \uc2 For Mr. Milner, a black who embodies many of the hopes of racial minorities here, the listing of Hartford as the fourth poorest city in America has been a boon of sorts.  \par \par \uc2 ''It helps in a way,'' he said. ''It tells the Federal Government where the need is. And it embarrasses our corporate community.'' Corporations play a part in Hartford matched by businesses in few, if any, other cities. Corporate largess pays for everything from parks to the arts. Corporations recently established an $11 million pool of low-interest housing loans and a $1 million pool for loans and grants to community development projects. One company, Cigna, even financed a $50,000 program to give summer jobs to members of youth gangs.  \par \par \uc2 But in the area of jobs, community expectations invariably exceed whatever the corporations provide. Mayor Miler estimates that 60 percent of those who work in Hartford live outside it. The number of commuters rises to nearly 90 percent for some insurance companies, the largest employers.  \par \par \uc2 Hartford, like many Northern cities, has undergone a transition from a manufacturing to a service economy. From 1970 to 1981 the city lost 8,000 manufacturing jobs - 40 percent of the total - but gained 13,000 service jobs, state labor statistics show.  \par \par \uc2 Jobs in the tobacco industry, once a major employer for Hartford's Hispanic residents, have declined by 15,000 in 20 years. The recent demise of the Consolidated Cigar farm in nearby Glastonbury is expected to cost 4,000 seasonal jobs.  \par \par \uc2 For people with white-collar skills, Hartford's transition meant more and better jobs. But for the city's residents, the blue-collar or agricultural workers, the change has been disastrous. Scraping for a Living  \par \par \uc2 Consider Vera and Thomas Benson, she disabled and he laid off from a janitor's job. They say they live on public aid, food stamps and money made collecting deposit bottles at 5 cents apiece. Their best day ever, Mr. Benson said, was $25.  \par \par \uc2 ''We've been saving them for the last two weeks,'' he added, ''so we can have a birthday dinner for our brother-in-law.'' Ismael Garcia said he worked on a tobacco farm near Hartford for five years before it closed last summer. Now he is studying English in a training program for former farm workers, but the program has been able to find jobs for only 32 of its 300 graduates.  \par \par \uc2 People like Mr. Garcia and Mr. and Mrs. Benson fall into a category that Hartford's civic and corporate leaders call the ''structurally unemployed.'' They are people with skills, but not the right ones in today's economy. Their plight has led to calls for massive job training - an approach supported by Mayor Milner, community groups such as the Asylum Hill Organizing Project and, increasingly, the corporate leaders themselves.  \par \par \uc2 ''We have too many people at the bottom of the scale, and we haven't done enough about them,'' said John Filer, the chairman of Aetna and a national leader in \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate\b0 \highlight\uc2  ''\b \highlight22\uc2 social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 '' investment. ''One of our future problems will be finding enough entry-level people with skills, so training is in our selfinterest.'' Basic Education Lagging  \par \par \uc2 Mr. Filer, whose company has a job-training center here, said he did not even mean specific computer or actuarial skills, but simply ''reading, writing, communicating well and understanding the work \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .''  \par \par \uc2 The apparent lack of applicants with such abilities has led to scrutiny of the Hartford public schools. Average scores by Hartford students on state basic skills tests are almost the lowest in Connecticut. And as long as they remain so, Mayor Milner said, ''personnel directors will recruit in the suburbs, as usual.''  \par \par \uc2 But the Superintendent of Schools, Hernan LaFontaine, said teachers were hindered by the school system's lack of money and by the poor home \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  of the students. The Superintendent said that when he arrived three years ago, Hartford schools had textbooks for only one in 10 pupils. A $2 million book-buying program ended the shortage, he said, but it was paid for by cutting $2 million worth of teaching positions, athletics and after-school tutorial programs.  \par \par \uc2 Hartford schools lost $1.4 million in Federal aid and grants last fall. Much of the money was restored recently, but not before the schools had eliminated remedial programs for 1,000 of 5,000 eligible pupils. Eighty percent of Hartford's 22,000 students come from poor homes, many without a working parent to be a role model for a youngster. 'The Proverbial Cycle'  \par \par \uc2 ''It's the proverbial cycle that's almost unbreakable,'' said Mr. LaFontaine. ''It isn't difficult to get the kids to look at a variety of fields. The difficult thing is getting them to realize what it takes to get those jobs, that it's not a magical transition.''  \par \par \uc2 Mr. LaFontaine is working with corporate officers on programs to ease that transition. Already several insurance companies have given computers and provided computer education in Hartford schools.  \par \par \uc2 But for a 29-year-old like John Robinson, all that came too late. Mr. Robinson, a Hartford high school graduate and an Army veteran, worked as a security guard at the Hartford Civic Center until the company that employed him lost the arena contract last year.  \par \par \uc2 Now, Mr. Robinson said, he earns $280 a month in a city ''workfare'' program, $217 of which goes to pay his rent. He commutes between several soup kitchens for his meals and continues to look for work.  \par \par \uc2 ''My basic skills are security and cooking,'' Mr. Robinson said, ''and there's nothing in them. I just figure in Hartford there are the fortunate and the unfortunate. And I am one of the unfortunate.''  \par \par \uc2 Illustrations: photo of new office buildings photo of Flora Hogg photo of Vera and Thomas Benson photo of bin for food donations  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gedu : \uc2 Education | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gjob : \uc2 Labor Issues | gcom : \uc2 Society/Community/Work\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjust