trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 J\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PG\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 PAGE A19\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  (Copyright (c) 1990, Dow Jones & Co., Inc.) \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  In "Conservatives Create It, and Liberals Spend It" (editorial page, Dec. 26), Martin Morse Wooster and James T. Bennett, in companion articles, are both about a decade behind the times in their thinking, labeling Right vs. Left like the old "White Hats vs. Black Hats." They suggest that foundations and corporations should fund only right-wing causes to reflect the thinking and values of their benefactors. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  Yes, Andrew Carnegie and John D. MacArthur were both entrepreneurial and they championed free enterprise. They dedicated their fortunes to foundations to do good works. Philanthropy -- that giving of both goods and services -- is a unique tradition in our free society. Americans place great value on generous giving to those less fortunate. Many view philanthropy as an essential element of a free society that strives for minimum governmental interference. If the private sector, through donations, did not address some of society's problems, the government would try to address them through higher taxes and more regulations. I suggest Carnegie and MacArthur would not be "spinning in their graves" but would applaud some of the creative approaches being taken by nongovernmental organizations to tackle problems that were not so apparent in their lifetimes. \par \par \uc2  Take, for example, protecting the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Conservation of our woodlands, water and wildlife should be a national priority. Most environmental organizations are no longer "knee-jerk obstructionists" but are staffed by well-educated biologists, chemists, hydrologists and other experts working to conserve our natural resources, with "conserve" meaning wise use, something every conservative should support. \par \par \uc2  Some consumers already are beginning to encourage \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  through their buying power, buying products and investing in accord with the corporations' evident concern for the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . These consumers are looking at long-term benefits for their children and grandchildren. If more corporations took a similar view and looked at the long-term impacts of their behavior rather than only the yearly bottom line, they might be surprised to find not only that it is cheaper to take care of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  first rather than to pay for cleanup later, but it also wins consumer support and loyalty. \par \par \uc2  Carol B. Waite \par \par \uc2  Director of Development \par \par \uc2  Defenders of Wildlife \par \par \uc2  Washington \par \par \uc2  --- \par \par \uc2  What Messrs. Wooster and Bennett wrote about was only a small part of a greater global paradox: The Capitalist Countries Created It and the Marxist/Statist Ones Spent it. The real culprits are not the foundations and the corporations but rather Western governments, in particular the U.S. Congress, in whose steps the foundations and corporations tend to follow. \par \par \uc2  "Never become friends with the Americans," an old sage advised before I came to the U.S. (I am originally from Ghana.) "Why?" I asked. "Because the West will sell you if you are a friend but will buy you if you are an enemy," he said. My response was: "Ah, but that's better than being an enemy of a black African dictator. For that will cost you a bullet in the head -- on credit." \par \par \uc2  Over the years, however, events confirmed some element of truth in the old sage's axiom. Much Western giving, euphemistically characterized as "development assistance," went to despicable Third World regimes that not only pursued arrant policies antithetical to Western values but also berated the West for its "imperialistic machinations." Even the Soviet Union received substantial U.S. "aid" -- grain shipments, disguised as legitimate trade but at fire-sale prices -- which permitted the Soviets to devote not less, but more of their scarce resources toward an arms buildup. As Paul Weyrich has observed, it was only when the Reagan administration refused further bailouts that the internal situation became so explosive that Mikhail Gorbachev could not ignore the insistent calls for reform to save the Soviet economy. The U.S. Congress and Western governments need to revamp their aid priorities by giving less to their "enemies" (Marxist and military dictatorships, especially those in black Africa) and the foundations and corporations will follow suit. \par \par \uc2  George B.N. Ayittey \par \par \uc2  Bradley Resident Scholar \par \par \uc2  The Heritage Foundation \par \par \uc2  Washington \par \par \uc2  --- \par \par \uc2  Mr. Wooster actually understates the distance the Carnegie Corporation has traveled from the ideas of its founder, Andrew Carnegie. For in his best-known works, two essays now referred to as "The Gospel of Wealth," Carnegie made clear what he thought philanthropists should do: "In bestowing charity, the main consideration should be to help those who will help themselves; to provide part of the means by which those who desire to improve may do so." By investing their "surplus" (as he put it) in libraries, universities, hospitals and such -- like, the wealthy would be performing the socially valuable task of providing "ladders upon which the aspiring can rise." \par \par \uc2  In his own time, Carnegie judged that $950 of every thousand dollars spent on "so-called charity" was wasted. If he were alive today and measured what the foundation he endowed (and many others) is doing against the goals he set forth, it is unlikely he would change his estimate. \par \par \uc2  Leslie Lenkowsky \par \par \uc2  President \par \par \uc2  Institute For Educational Affairs \par \par \uc2  Washington \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PUB\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 Dow Jones & Company\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b AN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Document j000000020011115dm1u003g0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row}\pard \ql \li-720\ri-720\widctlpar\aspalpha\as