r \uc2 In a market-based economy that recognizes the rights of private property, the only social responsibility of business is to create shareholder value and to do so legally and with integrity. Yet we do have important unresolved social challenges - from drug abuse to education and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  - that require collective action. Corporate management however has neither the political legitimacy nor the expertise to decide what is in the social interest. It is our form of government that provides the vehicle for collective choice via elected legislators and the judicial system.  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Whether \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  is advocated by political activists or the chief executive officer, the costs of these expenditures, which don't increase the value of the company or its stock, will be passed on to consumers by way of higher prices, or to employees as lower wages, or to shareholders as lower returns. Remember that employees also have shareholder interests by their participation in corporate pension funds. The essential issue is finding the most appropriate and effective way to solve social problems.  \par \par \uc2 During the last decade, an active market for takeovers has shown little tolerance for managements that are not attentive to shareholder value. Indeed, management's response to the threat of takeovers unlocked billions of dollars of value for the shareholders. It would, however, be a profound error to view increases in a company's value as concern just for the shareholders. Enlightened managers and public officials recognize that increases in stock prices reflect improvement in competitiveness - an issue that affects everyone with a stake in the company - or the economy.  \par \par \uc2 Nonetheless the chief executives of some of our largest companies contend that shareholder interests should not be their primary obligation. Just as ''\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 '' were the buzzwords of the 1960's and 70's, ''balancing the interests of 'stakeholders' '' are the latest code words for the same idea. Hicks B. Waldron, chairman of Avon Products, for example, contends: ''We have 40,000 employees and 1.3 million representatives around the world. We have a number of suppliers, institutions, customers, communities. None of them have the democratic freedom as shareholders do to buy or sell their shares. They have much deeper and much more important stakes in our company than our shareholders.''  \par \par \uc2 An approach that attempts to balance the interests of everyone with a stake in the company makes it easier for corporate managers to justify uneconomic diversification or overinvestment in a declining core business, since these moves are likely to be endorsed by people other than the shareholders. For organized labor, it means more jobs - in the short run. Suppliers enjoy the prospect of additional business, and the local community a larger tax base resulting from the increased size of the enterprise. Business decisions based on social criteria also often bring praise for the chief executive officer. It is precisely these decisions that subordinate shareholder interests and that trigger the much maligned corrective mechanisms of takeovers and restructuring.  \par \par \uc2 There is another view of stakeholders that is both consistent with and supportive of shareholder value: improved competitiveness, and in, the final analysis, socially responsible business behavior. This view recognizes that the company's continued existence and competitiveness depends on a long-term financial relationship with each of the groups that has an interest in the company. Employees want competitive wages and benefits. Customers want high-quality products and services at a competitive price. Suppliers and bondholders have financial claims that must be satisfied with cash when they fall due. Shareholders look for dividends and higher stock prices.  \par \par \uc2 If the company does not satisfy the financial claims of its constituents, it will cease to be viable. Employees, customers, and suppliers will simply withdraw their support. Thus, a going company must strive to enhance its long-term cash-generating ability. The ability of a company to distribute cash to its various constituent groups depends directly on its ability to generate cash from operating its businesses efficiently and on its ability to obtain any additional funds needed from the debt and equity markets. This long-term emphasis on cash flow as the basis for evaluating the maximum benefit for shareholders among arrangements with other interested parties, is the essence of the shareholder-value approach to management. There are inherent conflicts between shareholders and other groups, but management serves the long-term interests of its constituents best by enhancing its competitive position and thereby also increasing its economic value.  \par \par \uc2 The rash of takeovers and restructurings has led many to the politically expedient conclusion that shareholders are reaping substantial economic gains at the expense of other interested groups, especially employees. This adversarial view of the shareholder-stakeholder relationship is simplistic and in most cases inaccurate. Employees affected by a work-force reduction initiated as part of a takeover or corporate restructuring can usually point to superior competitors or to a management team that has failed to develop strategies that maximize shareholder value as the real culprit. In the end, it is the quality of management decision-making, coupled with an implementation process that fully embraces the contributions of all stakeholders, that leads to corporate success.  \par \par \uc2 Social investing, whether carried out by investment groups or by management, is not only at odds with the basic fiduciary duty to maximize value for shareholders, but also goes counter to corporate efforts to gain advantages in an increasingly competitive global marketplace. What can be more socially responsible than to build a sustainable competitive advantage? After all, it is competitiveness that will provide the jobs and the tax base needed for the accomplishment of social goals that are more effectively addressed by government than by the private sector.  \par \par \uc2 Photo: Alfred Rappaport (NYT/Jonathan Kirn); drawing  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfcpex : \uc2 FC&E Executive News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adju