\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  (Copyright (c) 1996, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.) \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  A standard view of the American corporation -- a view you could elicit without torture from millions of liberal-arts graduates and even some engineers -- is that it is an efficient deliverer of goods and services, yet also a wellspring of social injustice. Driven by a narrow calculus of profits, it is oblivious to the common good. And so, the litany goes, it degrades the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , promotes unsafe products, skimps on workplace safety and (current indictment No. 1) lays off workers who have given it years of service. \par \par \uc2  Embracing this view of the case, a sizable number of educated people say that corporations need to be made "socially responsible." In "The Heroic Enterprise" (Free Press, 246 pages, $25), John M. Hood tells them that they have got it all wrong -- that corporations do a lot for the common good just in the course of enriching their shareholders, and that efforts to push them back from the bottom line will be broadly counterproductive. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  His assault on the idea of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  begins as it must with some fundamentals laid down in 1970 by Milton Friedman in a justly famous New York Times Magazine article. Said Mr. Friedman: "There is one and only one social responsibility of business -- to use its resources and engage in activities designed to increase its profits," the only significant qualification being that it engage "in open and free competition without deception or fraud." Mr. Friedman argued that only real people, not artificial people like corporations, can have "responsibilities." And corporate managers, presumably real people, are also presumably agents for shareholders interested in profit maximization. \par \par \uc2  Mr. Hood takes you through the arguments swirling around these issues during the past quarter-century but leaves you thinking Mr. Friedman's position still makes sense. Somewhat surprisingly, given the centrality of the social-responsibility debate to his book, Mr. Hood does not seem much interested in the politics of the issue. He nowhere asks why corporations pushing job quotas for women and minorities tend to be rated high in "responsibility," why defense contractors are rated low, or how it came about that responsibilism as defined by those pushing it tends to look so much like a liberal agenda (conservative William Bennett's demands for family values in the record business being an interesting exception). \par \par \uc2  Mr. Hood has several strong chapters demonstrating the nexus between market incentives and socially desirable outcomes. Workplace safety has steadily improved over the years, not because of the Occupational Safety and Health Administration -- whose emergence in the 1970s apparently did nothing to decrease the rate of accidental deaths on the job -- but because employers have powerful incentives to avoid accidents. One incentive is the cost of insurance for workers' compensation. Another is a "risk premium" (measured in studies by Duke University economist W. Kip Viscusi) that translates into higher wage rates at plants and industries identified as unsafe. \par \par \uc2  The chapter on job discrimination leans hard on the analysis of Gary Becker of the University of Chicago, who long ago (1957) explained why corporations have incentives to minimize discrimination against women and minorities. Mr. Becker's main point is that companies screening out qualified job applicants are at a competitive disadvantage; he has also observed that this is why discrimination has been most persistent in monopolistic institutions (including government). But there is a bit of a wobble at one point in Mr. Hood's discrimination argument. Turning to the case for workplace diversity, he speaks enthusiastically of companies with the wit to see that they will benefit from assigning minority workers to jobs in minority areas they are trying to penetrate. A few paragraphs later, he slides into the awkward question of whether by the same token it might make sense to disfavor a minority worker in some situations. Should an experienced black employee be replaced by a Puerto Rican college graduate when the firm is operating in Hispanic markets? Mr. Hood's answer is no -- but he never explains why a steely-eyed profit-maximizer would reach the same conclusion (assuming a yes answer violates no civil rights). \par \par \uc2  Like Milton Friedman and Adam Smith, Mr. Hood wants his readers to distinguish between the motives driving business managers (obviously self-serving) and the consequences of their everyday behavior (broad gains in social welfare). The greatest strength of "The Heroic Enterprise" is the avalanche of examples of Smith's "invisible hand" at work in the modern corporation. Its workers and their families get rising incomes over time and the society gets Saran Wrap, magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), bar-code readers, surgical staples, on-line banking and lower food and computer prices. Only, or possibly not only, in America could so many educated people see this outcome as "irresponsibility." \par \par \uc2  --- \par \par \uc2  Mr. Seligman is a columnist for Fortune magazine. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nnam : \uc2 News Agency Material | nrvw : \uc2 Review\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \c