\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 J\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PG\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 A11\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  (Copyright (c) 1996, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.) \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CX\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  Correction \par \par \uc2  Amitai Etzioni is a sociologist. He was misidentified in a Letter to the Editor that ran on Aug. 8. (WSJ Aug. 20, 1996) \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  While in agreement with Herbert Stein's conclusion that a corporate executive's focus should be profit maximization ("Corporate America, Mind Your Own Business," editorial page, July 15), an argument long and persuasively championed by Milton Friedman, I am astonished at the seeming parochialism of an individual so long and intimately a part of the American political establishment. \par \par \uc2  Contrary to Mr. Stein's message that business should not do something "in the hope of thereby preventing government from doing it," anticipating and trying to ameliorate the impact of evolving government regulation through shrewd and timely pre-emptive action is the essence of astute management in today's legal \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Not long ago, for example, the tobacco industry supported a California legislative initiative to regulate smoking in public places in hopes of pre-empting more stringent municipal regulations. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  Mr. Stein dismisses some familiar varieties of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  as nothing more than "how to run a corporation efficiently to maximize profits," Thus, "corporations contributing to the United Givers Fund," or to his own American Enterprise Institute, apparently satisfy Mr. Stein's rigid cost-benefit calculus for distinguishing acceptable profit maximization from unacceptable altruism. When the expected benefits of pre-emptive action seem too remote or speculative to outweigh the costs, however, presumably business should take no action. Such a conclusion is shortsighted and, ultimately, self-defeating. \par \par \uc2  Perhaps Mr. Stein is partly blinded by the familiar economist's assumption of ceteris paribus. But, in a dynamic social and legal system, things never stay the same. In his 1905 epic "Law and Public Opinion in England," presaging the "New Deal" in the United States, English legal scholar A.V. Dicey lamented that in democratic political systems, law (with some lag time) invariably follows popular sentiment. Socialist Amitai Etzioni applied Dicey's principles to industry self-regulation in a 1992 Business and Society Review article "Corporate Behavior: Fewer Flaws Mean Fewer Laws," observing that "[w]hile some reregulation may be necessary, it would be better all around if business could raise its level of integrity without being made to do so." \par \par \uc2  A case in point that bears watching is the rapidly growing HMO industry. In response to a storm of public protest over sometimes premature hospital discharges of new mothers and their infants, some states have now mandated a minimum 48-hour hospital stay, and corresponding federal legislation has been endorsed by both political parties and the president. Earlier this month, HMO protests forced the Department of Health and Human Services to suspend enforcement of its March 27 rules limiting the use of financial incentives to reward doctors for cutting costs and controlling services to Medicare and Medicaid patients. But, only a day later, Massachusetts HMOs supported pending state legislation that would prohibit "any compensation arrangement with a health-care provider that may directly or indirectly have the effect of reducing or limiting services furnished to any person enrolled in a health plan." Is that \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  or just prudent, profit-maximizing business? \par \par \uc2  If corporate America simply minds its own business while ignoring the society in which it operates, the federal wage and price controls that Mr. Stein reviles will look pretty tame compared with future government regulation of business. \par \par \uc2  David Silverstein \par \par \uc2  Professor of Business Law \par \par \uc2  Suffolk University \par \par \uc2  Boston \par \par \uc2  --- \par \par \uc2  Mr. Stein makes a valuable point regarding the role of corporations in society's grander problems; he says that a corporation can "discharge its social responsibility when it maximize[s] profits." This proves true the statement made by a reporter describing Ben and Jerry's Homemade Ice Cream Co.'s ventures into social responsibility: "a business can fail as a force for social change and succeed as a business, but cannot succeed as a force for social change while failing as a business." Most definitely, a business helps society most when it has reached pareto efficiency -- significantly, an economic term describing maximization of benefits, not a public policy term. \par \par \uc2  But Mr. Stein seems to go too far in condemning the utility of social responsibility, even when the company is maximizing profits. The hypothetical situation he sets up -- one in which the morale of workers is helped by keeping old workers on board, thus making the situation a case of "efficiency" instead of corporate responsibility -- is far from the only situation in which corporations can have a responsible role. \par \par \uc2  In fact, true resource efficiency can be achieved only by considering the benefits to all "stakeholders," for lack of a more inclusive term, including the community. For instance, if a corporation is pareto efficient and has the option of, say, using a contractor that employs disabled people while not jeopardizing its own efficiency, the choice becomes a no-brainer: either use one and help out the community or use another contractor and get the same product without the community benefits. \par \par \uc2  In fact, using Mr. Stein's theory, if a company can continue to maximize its own profits while moving along the pareto frontier toward maximizing community goods (instead of only its own profits), the company will both succeed as a socially responsible force and leave no unrealized benefits either for themselves or for the community. In simple equation form: If community goods are greater than zero and are added to corporate benefits, total benefits must be greater than corporate benefits. Assuming (correctly) that corporate leaders are not the cold-hearted, stodgy tycoons that cartoons and comedians stereotype them to be, why would a company refuse such opportunities, even if they did derive from the drawing boards of the dreaded federal government? \par \par \uc2  If the corporation is to be treated as an entity under law and consequently accept rights granted to it, it must also shoulder certain responsibilities; even if this means responsibilities that go beyond, though never instead of, its own profits. \par \par \uc2  Eric Gottesman \par \par \uc2  Nashua, N.H. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i951 : \uc2 Health Care\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c41 : \uc2 Management Issues | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | ghea : \uc2 Health | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | ncrx : \uc2 Corrected Items | nedc : \uc2 Commentary/Opinion | nlet : \uc2 Letter | nrgn : \uc2 Routine General News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 namz : \uc2 North America | usa : \uc