aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  c. 1996 New York Times Company \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  BUSINESS is being urged to embrace ''corporate citizenship.'' Just as with the individual citizen, the good corporate citizen is expected to act with integrity and be socially responsible, which has come to mean not only acting responsibly in fulfilling its primary function of producing goods and services, but also ''doing good'' in seemingly unrelated areas -- by improving working conditions, for example, for the employees of overseas suppliers. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  Companies like Levi Strauss and Body Shop International have long been considered in the vanguard of the movement for greater \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Now, however, they are being joined by different and often much larger companies that also aspire to be known as good corporate citizens. A highlight of last year's annual conference of Business for Social Responsibility was a presentation by Robert B. Shapiro, chief executive of Monsanto, on business's role in protecting the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  At the coming conference in New York this fall, presenters will include Citibank, Home Depot and Nynex. \par \par \uc2  President Clinton is also promoting corporate citizenship. In May, he held a conference at Georgetown University lauding the virtues of business efforts to tackle social problems, devoting a day to presentations by companies that demonstrate the principles of corporate citizenship. \par \par \uc2  But these increased efforts by business worry some economists -- and here is the first potential pitfall of corporate citizenship and cause for caution for those who promote it within their own organizations. Neoclassical economists have long railed against \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . It is the business of business to maximize profits, they say, and for corporate America to address other objectives diverts it from its most important function of putting people and resources to work efficiently. \par \par \uc2  Company shareholders often agree, particularly if they believe it's their money that's being used to address social issues. In his aptly titled book, ''Mean Business,'' the corporate turnaround specialist Albert J. Dunlap says ''you're in business for one thing -- to make money.'' If you have another agenda, he says, ''join Rotary International.'' \par \par \uc2  One can argue that the failure of government to solve many social problems makes corporate action welcome. More business involvement in social problems and less government input may not be such a bad idea, even if it entails reduced efficiency of the economy. \par \par \uc2  Wall Street, however, may not buy this. A better answer is that executives who rely on the easy, do-nothing reassurances of neoclassical economists simply have it wrong. \par \par \uc2  Economists' assumptions about markets often do not hold. Moreover, managers often choose to ''do the right thing'' over unadulterated profit maximization, and enlightened self-interest can result in long-term profitability. Doing good may be good for business. Doing bad may be bad for business. \par \par \uc2  Consider an example discussed at the President's conference. \par \par \uc2  At Starbucks, health and retirement security is promoted by providing health benefits and an employee stock ownership plan for all workers, most of whom are part-time. \par \par \uc2  Is this wasteful, because the resources could have been used more profitably elsewhere? Of course not. And Starbucks succeeded in addressing a social issue -- health care -- and received economic rewards. \par \par \uc2  Employee benefits at Starbucks are far more extensive, and more expensive, than those of competitors. But programs that were developed out of a sense of social responsibility have also resulted in an annual staff turnover rate of 55 percent, versus an industry norm of 400 percent. Low  turnover reduces hiring and training costs and increases the likelihood of better customer service. \par \par \uc2  Just as important, Starbucks benefits from a reputation for being socially responsible. A survey by Walker Research found that 88 percent of consumers indicated they were much or somewhat more likely to buy from a company that is socially responsible and a good corporate citizen, if the quality, service and price are equal to that of competitors. \par \par \uc2  Good news, perhaps, yet herein lies the second potential pitfall of corporate citizenship and cause for caution. Consider the criticism that comes from within the \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  movement. \par \par \uc2  Business Ethics, a magazine that more typically promotes the virtues of corporate citizenship, published an article on the Body Shop that questioned various business practices and the public perceptions of its products as naturally based. \par \par \uc2  A storm of adverse publicity descended on a company that had always been treated with reverence. An independent social performance audit undertaken at the company's request confirmed a number of the article's criticisms. \par \par \uc2  While the accuracy of some of the criticisms may be debated, there is still an underlying concern that companies associated with social responsibility may trade on such an association and charge an ''integrity premium.'' The association invites close scrutiny, and failings in one area make people wonder if claims of social responsibility are hypocritical, even if a company's activities in other areas are exemplary. \par \par \uc2  NOT only are these organizations especially vulnerable to attack, they are also run by people who are not infallible and are in jobs that often involve conflicts of values. While it is important to strive for consistently good conduct across a company's activities, this may be impossible to guarantee. What matters is whether the company did all it could do. Intent counts. \par \par \uc2 \f2 \par Of course, determining intent is not straightforward, and critics\par often attempt to have it both ways when confronted with examples of\par corporate citizenship also serving a company's interests. But examples\par abound of \f28 \b \highlight22\uc2 \f2 corporate social responsibility\f28 \b0 \highlight\uc2 \f2  that is clearly not primarily\par motivated by profit maximization -- including, to further allay the\par fears of neoclassical economists, plenty of successful companies in\par competitive markets. May their numbers continue to grow!\par   About the Author: N. Craig Smith is associate professor of marketing\par at the Georgetown School of Business.\par \f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 \par 04:06 EDT September 8, 1996\par \f28 \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 213179\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 sbcoff : \uc2 Starbucks Corp\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i64 : \uc2 Retail/Wholesale | i654 : \uc2 Specialty Stores\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clverta