rowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Virginia Matthews on saving corporate reputations.\par \par \uc2 Public repentance for a corporation's previous sins is the best route to achieving the forgiveness of customers and shareholders, delegates to a conference on company reputation will be told on Wednesday.*\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Mark Goyder, director of the Centre for Tomorrow's Company, the corporate-funded think tank, will tell the conference that defensiveness, arrogance or lies in the face of problems can do untold damage to a reputation, while an apology - still rare in the business world - will usually go some way towards making amends.\par \par \uc2 Goyder believes that Shell, which came under attack last year over the disposal of the Brent Spar and its activities in Nigeria, has taken an important step "towards rehabilitation" by publicly declaring its support for human rights and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . While there will still be many, he says, who decry it, Shell's re-writing of its business principles is tantamount to a show of "corporate repentance".\par \par \uc2 Next week's London conference examines the performance of companies voted "most admired" in an annual survey by Management Today, the UK journal. The present holder of the title is Tesco, the supermarket group. Other top 10 companies include Marks and Spencer, SmithKline Beecham and British Petroleum.\par \par \uc2 At the other end of the scale is British Gas, which comes 254th in the survey of 260 companies. Last year it ranked 216th. Others near the bottom are Sears, House of Fraser, Kwik Save and Cordiant.\par \par \uc2 Simon Lewis, director of corporate affairs at British Gas, will tell the conference that "while it has made mistakes in the past", the company, now operated by Centrica and open to competition for the first time, can and must regain a solid reputation. "We are only too aware that in the past, we failed to be customer-focused at a time when it was vital to be so and, as a result of this, our brand's reputation has taken a real beating," he will say.\par \par \uc2 "I believe that the lack of a customer focus led directly to problems such as incorrect bills, criticism over the fact that customers couldn't get through to our energy centres on the telephone and to all the well-documented problems with direct debit accounts being debited several times over."\par \par \uc2 A #100m investment programme last year in new technology, better systems and in more staff will, according to Lewis, go some way to restoring public confidence, but he fears that its lacklustre reputation may prove hard to challenge. However, he believes that "the perception of British Gas now lags behind the reality".\par \par \uc2 Too many businesses believe that they can "throw money" at their reputations, according to Goyder. He believes that "clever marketing" of an individual brand can in no way make up for "short-sighted management".\par \par \uc2 While British Telecommunications once had a reputation for arrogance and inefficiency, it now ranks number 18. Goyder believes it was right to make improvements to service before blowing its own trumpet to customers, shareholders and the City. Getting a large proportion of the public call boxes to work was, he says, a defining moment in the battle for BT's now-enviable reputation.\par \par \uc2 While financial results will always be an important litmus test of a company's achievements, Goyder believes that Barings, for example, made the mistake of allowing its results to become "more important than its values". As a result, it was possible for one trader to destroy its reputation.\par \par \uc2 At its best, a company's reputation can lead to unprompted advocacy by customers, Bob Worcester, Mori chairman, another speaker. "Our research shows that 15% of the British public will spontaneously recommend M&S to their friends, while only 1% of the country will do the same for Dixons. That sort of word-of-mouth, free advertising is worth millions to any company and will stand them in very good stead if there is ever a crisis."\par \par \uc2 One of the keys to reputation is an open style of management and a commitment to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Goyder believes that Perrier's refusal to admit that there was a problem with benzene contamination in its bottled water several years ago was an example of a company which reacted to a crisis with "ill-advised secrecy".\par \par \uc2 The decision not to talk about what had happened merely compounded the damage and "prolonged its agony".\par \par \uc2 Openness and honesty with shareholders, customers and employees alike differentiates "yesterday's company from tomorrow's," according to Goyder, who quotes the chief executive of the Birmingham Midshires Building Society as one of a rare breed of company bosses who puts his own home telephone number on his company's complaints forms.\par \par \uc2 *Further details of conference, organised by Management Today in association with PR Week: Haymarket Conferences 0171 413 4116\par \par \uc2 Copyright Financial Times Limited 1997. All Rights Reserved.\par \par \uc2 Not Available for Re-dissemination. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c15 : \uc2 Performance | c152 : \uc2 Earnings Projections | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 eecz : \uc2 European Union Countries | eurz : \uc2 Europe | uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PUB\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 The Financial Times Limited (AAIW/EIW)\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\c