{  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b \highlight22\uc2 ENVIRONMENT\b0 \highlight\uc2  VIEWPOINT - PETER KNIGHT and SIMON PROPPER - Independent auditing of social and environmental performance should not be left to the Big Five accountancy firms.\par \par \uc2 Accountants are ingenious at finding new ways to use their bean-counting expertise. Auditing financial statements will always be their bread-and-butter business, but the Big Five accountancy firms are salivating over the potentially lucrative opportunities offered by the two big Es: e-commerce and \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 At issue is the independent auditing of systems, processes and reporting by companies that want to proclaim their honesty and integrity to an increasingly sceptical public. Examples range from checking payment systems on the internet to compiling, writing and verifying \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social reports. But are accountants the right people to give us the assurance we seek? Do they have the necessary skills, culture and, most important, perceived integrity to impress critics of business? We think not.\par \par \uc2 Accountants will be needed if the proposed systems to trade greenhouse gas permits (mainly carbon dioxide), under the UN's climate change convention, is to work properly. They will provide the much-needed reassurance to facilitate this trade.\par \par \uc2 But our concerns are about the Big Five's intentions to muscle in on \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social reporting. This is the growing trend among companies voluntarily to divulge data and information about their emissions, wastes, and prosecutions - what has become known as their "environmental performance". About 500 companies worldwide now publish such reports and certain governments, especially those in the European Union, are keen to encourage them.\par \par \uc2 Lately, some large companies - Aracruz, BP, Shell, and Rio Tinto among them - have been broadening the scope of their reporting to include \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues, such as employment practices, bribery cases, community activities, charitable donations and the like.\par \par \uc2 No universally accepted formats exist for such reporting, although some are emerging. Most \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  reports conform to de facto standards that have sprung from guidelines laid down by trade associations and campaign groups. Social reporting is in its infancy, but there is a considerable pressure for companies to report on all three performances: financial, environmental and social.\par \par \uc2 The Big Five are keen to verify the data and assertions made in these reports, as they have begun to do for Shell and BP. The main function of the reports is to communicate with non-business interests: opinion formers, legislators, non-governmental organisations, investors, customers, and so forth. One problem with the publications is that few of the sceptical audiences believe a word of what they read. Opinion formers, such as legislators and campaign groups, generally welcome the efforts but take the figures with a sack of salt.\par \par \uc2 The main thrust of the Big Five's sales pitch is that it is only accountants accredited to their professional bodies who can provide top-notch verification.\par \par \uc2 This is all enterprising stuff, but it is difficult to believe that domination by the Big Five is good for reporting. Yes, we need the frameworks and the methodologies. But what we need most are verifiers with a strong commitment to the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the technical expertise to see where huge businesses are going wrong. Very expensive bean counters checking systems is not enough.\par \par \uc2 There is another more significant concern. The ingrained culture of the accountancy firms is too business-friendly to impress critical outsiders. Recent, and often incomprehensible legal mumbo jumbo verification statements too tedious to quote, support the suspicion that the accountant/client relationship is just too cozy.\par \par \uc2 What accountants - and some of those who employ them - fail to understand is that critical audiences trust accountants even less than the companies they audit. Furthermore, these publics want verifiers to share any criticisms with readers as well as the businesses that are paying for the service. Otherwise the whole costly verification exercise is viewed as men in suits sharing funny handshakes - the Big Five giving businesses the High Five.\par \par \uc2 Accountants, perhaps, should be looking to form verification partnerships with non-governmental organisations that the public trusts - at least then some of the exorbitant fees paid by the client might end up doing some good rather than overloading the Big Five's coffers.\par \par \uc2 Verifiers also need to understand the communications process and how their role can both enhance and hinder the effectiveness of reporting. Whatever strengths accountants might have, communications is clearly not one of them. Would you, for example, pay PricewaterhouseCoopers to devise a snappy new company name?\par \par \uc2 For \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social reporting to succeed and grow, we need a credible, cost-efficient vehicle to encourage verification among more than the multinationals. We need a VW Golf - solid, economical and reliable - not a Mercedes S Class with "Big 5" as a number plate.\par \par \uc2 * Peter Knight and Simon Propper are co-directors of Environmental Context, a London-based consultancy advising business on sustainable development. E-mail: knightp@compuserve.com.\par \par \uc2 Copyright Financial Times Limited 1999. All Rights Reserved.\par \par \uc2 Not Available for Re-dissemination. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i836 : \uc2 Accounting | iacc : \uc2 Accounting/Consulting\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c21 : \uc2 Output/Production | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | genv : \uc2 Environmental News | grisk : \uc2 Risk News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\wid