o\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 MANAGEMENT SOCIAL RESPONSIBILITY - BP is facing criticism for its response to continuing conflict in an oil-rich region of Colombia. Richard Lapper reports.\par \par \uc2 Geologists use the term "compression \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 " to describe the complex rock formation in the oil-rich Colombian department of Casanare. It could equally be applied to conditions above ground.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Increasing social tension and guerrilla violence is making BP's experience in the region - site of one of Latin America's biggest oil discoveries in 20 years - a testing ground for social responsibility by companies in parts of the developing world.\par \par \uc2 An unpublished report, prepared by Oxfam, Save the Children Fund and other non-governmental organisations, accuses BP - now merged with Amoco of the US - of unwittingly aggravating the problems and says the company should do more to campaign against human rights abuses.\par \par \uc2 "BP has gone further than its strict legal obligations ... and its approach to community affairs developed significantly throughout the 1990s," says the report. "[But] commitment to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  must be judged on outcome and not intention."\par \par \uc2 Oil has drawn thousands of poor migrants into the area, increasing pressure on infrastructure. The population of Yopal, the department's biggest town, increased from 4,800 in 1973 to 36,500 in 1993.\par \par \uc2 "Casanare has attracted migrants for more than 20 years, long before oil arrived. However, the scale of things has changed," says Roger Cartwright, director of Latin American affairs at BP Amoco. "We have seen a gold rush effect since early after our arrival."\par \par \uc2 BP has tried to ensure its investment of more than $2bn ( #1.2bn) benefits the population as a whole. Royalties of about $100m a year go directly to the government of Casanare.\par \par \uc2 The company spends significant sums on social projects: it has pumped $25m into education, training and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  since 1992; installed a plant to supply drinking water for more than 14,000 people; promoted small business; and given priority to employing local people and buying from local companies.\par \par \uc2 However, the rising violence has exposed alleged shortcomings. For more than 20 years Casanare and neighbouring areas have endured incidents, including regular attacks on foreign-owned installations by the National Liberation Army (ELN), one of a number of leftwing guerrilla groups active in Colombia.\par \par \uc2 In the past three years, rightwing paramilitary armies, financed by the drugs industry, have also stepped up their activities. BP's extensive security arrangements to protect its personnel and investments have allowed production to proceed with only limited interruption. But Mr Cartwright acknowledges that the situation has "got a lot more complicated".\par \par \uc2 The violence has made it difficult for BP to co-exist with local people even on the terms that are typical when a big multinational company moves into a small community, let alone establish the more positive links it is seeking as part of its social responsibility policy.\par \par \uc2 "Casanare is not Colombia's worst nor its best region in terms of conflict, but the fear of abduction and extortion exists and hinders more direct and spontaneous involvement with the community," says Mr Cartwright. "If we were developing normally, we'd have all our people down there integrated seamlessly into the community."\par \par \uc2 The agencies say the growth of paramilitary violence has wrongfooted the company. According to their report, the company has relied too much on the local police force and military, accused by human rights groups of co-operating or turning a blind eye to the rightwing groups.\par \par \uc2 "The problem is that BP has been under explicit threat from the leftwing guerrillas," says Sophia Tickell, who works with Oxfam on corporate and social governance issues and is joint author of the report. "They have built up security around that threat and haven't anticipated the wider violence in the region."\par \par \uc2 Problems have been generated by accusations that BP was complicit in the murders of local activists opposed to its operations and that the company's security contractors employed members of paramilitary gangs.\par \par \uc2 Early in 1998 a year-long inquiry by the Colombian prosecutor cleared BP of involvement but the episode has generated bad publicity.\par \par \uc2 The report says the company must adopt a "robust stance in defence of human rights, including outspoken calls for full investigations into cases of human rights violations and a fully operational judicial system".\par \par \uc2 It needs to improve its vetting procedures to ensure it does not employ or contract paramilitaries, and to develop training for its staff and contractors to denounce abuses when they occur.\par \par \uc2 Above all, the agencies say, BP needs to ensure its policies are given as much importance at local level as at head office in London.\par \par \uc2 "We recognise you can't just wave a magic wand and make all the problems go away and we know that BP has come a long way," says Ms Tickell. "The starting point for a lot of what BP has been doing is public relations but some of the policy hasn't filtered down to BP's operation in Colombia."\par \par \uc2 Mr Cartwright stresses that much of the criticism fails to recognise practical constraints facing BP. "It is not as black and white as it is often portrayed," he says.\par \par \uc2 Even so, he accepts there is room for improvement. "We haven't made fundamental mistakes but with 20-20 hindsight, you could always do things better."\par \par \uc2 Copyright Financial Times Limited 1999. All Rights Reserved.\par \par \uc2 Not Available for Re-dissemination. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 bp : \uc2 BP PLC\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i1 : \uc2 Energy | i13 : \uc2 Crude Oil/Natural Gas | i1300003 : \uc2 Crude Petroleum Extraction\cell \pard \ql \li0\r