entatives to demand protection for "God's green earth".\par \par \uc2 The Interfaith Center on Corporate Responsibility, a group that says it holds more than $100bn in pension funds, is demanding action on global warming from 12 large US corporations.\par \par \uc2 Last week, the group added Exxon Mobil to its list of targeted companies, joining a coalition of 42 other religious and environmental organisations in 17 states. The centre intends to press Exxon Mobil to reform corporate practices that "contribute to global warming".\par \par \uc2 The centre, composed mainly of religious investors, has been urging Exxon Mobil to invest heavily in "clean, efficient and reliable energy sources". It also wants the company to acknowledge that human activity is causing global warming and to "cease its campaign of misinformation to confuse the public and policymakers about the facts regarding this severe environmental threat".\par \par \uc2 "Exxon Mobil's position of denial and misinformation on global warming puts all of creation at risk, and we simply cannot stand by and let them do that," said Sister Pat Daly of the centre.\par \par \uc2 Exxon Mobil is a member of the Global Climate Coalition, a group of companies that has become a particular target for environmental activists. The GCC says it promotes voluntary reduction of greenhouse gases, but it wants "unfettered debate" on the theory of climate change.\par \par \uc2 Exxon Mobil said the Interfaith Center had misinterpreted its policies. "Our position on global warming is that we think we need a dialogue on how good the science is. But we can never get to that discussion."\par \par \uc2 It said Exxon Mobil was a company that based its business on technology and science. "We will have the same rigour on global warming as we do when we are running a 3D seismic off West Africa."\par \par \uc2 The Interfaith Center also made Ford a target until the vehicle maker agreed to withdraw from the GCC last month.\par \par \uc2 Still on the centre's hit list are: Allegheny Energy, Chevron, CSX, Duke Energy, Eastman Chemical, Mobil, Norfolk Southern, Texaco, Goodyear, Cinergy and General Motors.\par \par \uc2 The 29-year-old group of Protestant, Catholic and Jewish institutional investors believes it can profitably merge social and environmental values with investment decisions. It is part of a growing "\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  movement" that includes labour unions.\par \par \uc2 Social Investment Forum, an investors' association, last year said nearly one in every seven dollars under investment management in the US - more than $2,000bn - was actively involved in the \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  movement.\par \par \uc2 The Interfaith Center believes companies that take moral and ethical stands will prosper most.\par \par \uc2 Its members are long-term investors that need solid returns to run parishes, synagogues and schools, pay pensions for employees and help the poor.\par \par \uc2 Most of its environmental actions are similar. In one shareholder resolution it asked Texaco to report to investors by next August on greenhouse gas emissions from the company's operations and products. It asked for information on the company's financial exposure resulting from the costs of reducing emissions and potential liability for damages associated with climate change.\par \par \uc2 Sister Pat said the centre had had successes in many areas. Last year it submitted 153 shareholder resolutions, challenging corporations on everything from sweatshops and "racist" advertising to the safety of healthcare products and withdrawal from Burma.\par \par \uc2 Copyright Financial Times Limited 2000. All Rights Reserved. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\t