cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  (Copyright (c) 2000, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.) \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  Clive Belgeonne, a 41-year-old teacher from Manchester, is exactly the kind of do-gooding, left wing, environmentally concerned activist that the financial establishment loves to mock. Five years as a voluntary overseas worker in West Africa and Latin America made Mr. Belgeonne determined to use his investments to put a stop to what he calls "global inequity". \par \par \uc2  From his mortgage to his mutual fund right down to his seven-year-old son Adam's tiny savings account, every penny of Mr. Belgeonne's financial assets is screened for potential environmental and social impact. "I want to lead a sustainable life," he says. "In the words of the American Indians, I want to tread more lightly upon the earth." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  For years, the majority of money invested in "ethical" or "socially responsible" funds has come from individuals like Mr. Belgeonne who have direct experience of Third World poverty or environmental pollution. Financial analysts mostly dismissed the phenomenon as the realm of cranks and moralists. If you limit your investment universe, they pronounced, you inevitably hurt your return. \par \par \uc2  Lately though, the men in pinstripes are having to eat their words. Many ethical funds have significantly outperformed their mainstream equivalents; the U.S.-based Domini 400 Social Index, for instance, 10 years old in May, has beaten the S&P 500 each year since 1997. It notched up a 20.3% return in 1999 and a three-year annualized return of 30.2%, ahead of the S&P 500, which rose 17.9% and 27.4%, respectively. \par \par \uc2  Individual investors should take note; maybe it's possible to make money and be virtuous at the same time. It's already proving an irresistible combination for many European and U.S. savers. Although socially responsible money as a proportion of total mutual-fund assets is still miniscule, demand is rising fast. Traditional investment houses are responding by bringing out more socially responsible products. In Spain, there were seven new funds by the end of 1999 and in Sweden there are 20 existing funds. The rest of Europe boasts another 30 funds, excluding the U.K., which has more than 40 funds and GBP 3 billion (4.8 billion euros) under management. \par \par \uc2  Pension funds are coming under increasing pressure to declare an ethical, environmental or socially responsible aim. From July 3rd, all U.K. pension funds will be obliged to state whether or not they have a policy on the matter. According to Ivo Knoepfel, head of rating at Sustainable Asset Management, a Swiss sustainable-asset manager, both the Norwegian and Swiss governments are exploring ways to follow Britain's example. \par \par \uc2  Investing in a socially responsible manner is far from straightforward, however. Attempts to make companies behave better using shareholder pressure and voting power are often doomed to failure by the fact that the amount of money managed ethically is still relatively small. \par \par \uc2  "Arms control is down to the politicians," says Robin Geffen, a fund manager at Orbitex Investments in London, a traditional investment house. "We as fund managers can't do anything about it. If you look at the most powerful shareholders in these companies they're hard-nosed financial institutions who only care about maximizing returns." \par \par \uc2  Although the numbers on SRI investing look good so far, no one in the SRI community can pin down exactly why it is that companies with sound environmental and social policies have outperformed. \par \par \uc2  "There's a causal problem here," says Seb Beloe, a senior consultant at SustainAbility, a London-based consultancy that advises companies on environmental policy. "It might be that the companies who do well and perform financially are those that have the money to spend on thinking about society and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , not the other way around." \par \par \uc2  In addition, he says, European ethical funds are forced to rely almost entirely on information from the companies themselves to judge their environmental and social credentials, unlike in the U.S. where more objective sources are available. "We need more rigorous, audited information," says Mr. Beloe. \par \par \uc2  For now, though, the SRI community is riding high on a newfound confidence that their way of investing not only benefits the planet and its inhabitants, but that it can match or even beat mainstream funds. Persuaded by facts like the outperformance of the Domini Index, the Dow Jones Sustainability Index and the MPI Social Index, investing professionals are being won over. At a conference on socially responsible investing hosted in Lisbon by the European Commission in May, PGGM, the second-largest pension fund in the Netherlands with more than $46 billion under management, announced that it would start to manage money according to SRI principles. "We believe that it increases returns," said Alfred Kool, a representative of PGGM. \par \par \uc2  But isn't corporate bad behavior just a way to make more money? According to proponents of SRI, environmental and social policies are actually good for business in the long term. First and foremost, they're an indicator of management quality. Then there's their positive impact on employee retention and productivity. Marc Brykman, managing director of Shell in Belgium, voiced his support for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  at the Lisbon conference. "Our staff turnover is low because of our social and environmental policies," he said. \par \par \uc2  Far better to spend some money on avoiding the disaster in the first place. "Shell lost 30% of its market share in Germany after Brent Spar and it took them eighteen months to get it back," says Mr. Cusack, CEO of Innovest Strategic Value Advisors, a New York-based consultancy. Last year, Coca-Cola Enterprises took a $103 million (110 million euros) charge after a contamination scare in Belgium and France forced the company to recall its products. The direct financial cost was compounded by the damage done to the company's reputation in Europe by then-Chief Executive Douglas Ivester's sluggish handling of the crisis; it took him 10 days to fly to Brussels and apologize. \par \par \uc2  To be sure, evidence of SRI outperformance is a long way from being conclusive. There simply isn't enough historical data yet to produce meaningful correlations, and in any case, past performance isn't a guide to the future. It may be that SRI funds have done well only because they've been overweight in technology; tech stocks are generally favored by the SRI world since, unlike many smoke-stack industries, they don't hurt the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and they tend to have an enlightened approach to their staff due to the difficulty of attracting and keeping them. \par \par \uc2  For the moment it appears that environmental factors are more closely tied to financial performance than social issues. "It may take another ten years to prove," says Mr. Cusack. "In the meantime a lot of financial professionals are saying `wait and see'." \par \par \uc2  Annette Little, a marine biologist from Cambridge, U.K., doesn't want to wait. She dives among coral reefs and watches them getting bleached as sea temperatures rise. "If we have gradual climactic change then the reefs will move further north," says Ms. Little, "but if fluctuations are erratic then the coral may get squeezed out." At the same time, she feels comfortable these days that she won't lose out by investing in an environmentally friendly way. "I don't want to take any risks," she says. "Ecologically sound funds have performed well." \par \par \uc2  Newcomers to the socially responsible arena have some difficult choices to make. The first question to answer, of course, is what principles you want to impose on your investment portfolio. If you have trouble finding a fund that matches them all, try a Web site called {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.ethicalservices.co.uk/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.ethicalservices.co.uk}}}\uc2  which allows you to mark various boxes -- armaments, genetically modified organisms, nuclear power, animal testing, etc. -- to indicate which activities you want to preclude from your investment portfolio. The site also enables the user to choose ethical values -- recycling, education, renewable energy, for instance, -- so as to select a fund which favors companies that are particularly strong in these areas. \par \par \uc2  Investors should watch out for funds that use an ethical overlay as little more than a marketing tool. Those that screen companies for financial performance first and then choose the ones with the best SRI characteristics are unlikely to be as rigorous as those which start off by judging their ethical, social or environmental criteria. \par \par \uc2  "Some funds are cheap and shoddily put together," says Mr. Beloe. One European SRI fund, according to Craig Mackenzie, director of the Ethics Unit at Friends Ivory & Sime, markets itself as ethical on the basis that it doesn't invest in companies that participate in illegal activities. \par \par \uc2  SRI funds differ greatly in how they approach their ethical agendas. The older funds tend to be more negative; they simply outlaw certain industries and companies. These days, though, more tolerant, dialogue-oriented approaches are coming to the fore. "A lot of the old ethical industry developed from the radical left wing and religious groups and so concentrated on negative criteria," says Kim Moeller, director of Oxford Research, an SRI research organization based in Copenhagen. "But SRI now isn't about exclusion, it's about active shareholding." \par \par \uc2  Norway's Storebrand-Scudder Environmental Value Fund, for instance, selects companies that are ranked in the top 30% of every industry sector based on sustainability criteria. A positive "best of sector" approach means that bad companies have an incentive to clean up their act, say SRI providers. Other funds take an active approach, trying to persuade company managements to improve their policies. Even the more radical among SRI investors approves. "Global capitalism is unlikely to disappear overnight," says Mr. Belgeonne. "So you've got to engage in the debate." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i81502 : \uc2 Trusts/Funds/Financial Vehicles | i8150211 : \uc2 Unit Trusts/Mutual Funds | iinv : \uc2 Investing/Securities\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c12 : \uc2 Corporate Crime/Legal/Judicial | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ecat : \uc2 Economic News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gcrim : \uc2 Crime/Courts | gpersf : \uc2 Personal Finance | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nnam : \uc2 News Agency Material\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15