h15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2000 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Responsible social and environmental behaviour has become an imperative for companies rather than something that is "nice to do", according to a survey to be published today at the Prince of Wales Business Leaders' Forum in London, writes Alison Maitland.\par \par \uc2 The survey of 100 institutional investors, regulators, parliamentarians, business journalists and non-governmental organisations in France, Germany and the UK, points to rising expectations of what constitutes good corporate practice.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Sixty-six per cent of respondents strongly agree that corporate responsibility will be important in their assessment of companies in the future, and 64 per cent agree strongly that it will affect their own decisions.\par \par \uc2 There is strong support for the idea that good practice will increasingly affect a company's share price, with 76 per cent agreeing, against 14 per cent who oppose the idea.\par \par \uc2 The survey was carried out by Research International for Burston-Marsteller, the communications agency.\par \par \uc2 Asked what \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  represents, 71 per cent define it as "leadership that looks beyond the short term".\par \par \uc2 Having a good record on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  is now seen as a minimum requirement when assessing a company, while respect for employees emerges as the single biggest factor causing respondents to admire a company. Charitable giving is viewed with suspicion if a company is not pursuing good practice on social and environmental issues.\par \par \uc2 There is disagreement about the scrutiny that dotcom companies face. Nineteen per cent think corporate responsibility has as much of an impact on dotcoms as on established companies, and 18 per cent say it will eventually have an impact. But 19 per cent believe dotcoms are unaffected or little affected by the issue. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c41 : \uc2 Management Issues | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ad