president of BITC. This week, all finalists in the Programme Impact Award categories will receive Impact Endorsement Marks, attesting that their community programmes have had a measurable effect on society.\par \par \uc2 The Impact Endorsement Marks will be presented by Kim Howells, who earlier this year became the first minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  as part of the government's efforts to raise the profile of issues relating to business involvement in the community.\par \par \uc2 There are two special awards - one for innovation and the other the Prince of Wales's Ambassador Award to an individual demonstrating outstanding leadership in \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  - and nine other categories. These are:\par \par \uc2 Business Excellence\par \par \uc2 Impact on Society Award: for commitment to improving and reporting overall impact on society; Business in the \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  Award: for sustainable environmental performance; Community Investment Award: for overall impact on the community, employees and the company; Diversity Award: for companies striving to attract and utilise a truly diverse workforce,\par \par \uc2 Programme Impact\par \par \uc2 Enterprising Communities Award: for the social and economic regeneration of local communities;\par \par \uc2 Power in Partnership Award: for collaborative action involving the public, private and voluntary sectors;\par \par \uc2 Investing in Young People Award: for raising educational achievement and employability skills;\par \par \uc2 Focused Action Award: for innovative action in tackling social issues;\par \par \uc2 Cause Related Marketing Award: for using the power of brands in conjunction with charities to address social issues.\par \par \uc2 Criteria for assessing the Awards for Excellence is based on the Business Excellence Model. Taken together, the award categories illustrate the rich mixture of activities that are now included in corporate social programmes.\par \par \uc2 But the context in which these programmes take place is becoming increasingly complex and challenging.\par \par \uc2 Last year's World Trade Organisation conference in Seattle, and the International Monetary Fund and World Bank meetings in Washington this spring, unleashed an angry coalition of interests broadly united by hostility to global corporate power.\par \par \uc2 More peacefully, but just as significantly, surveys show that growing numbers of consumers, employees and opinion formers expect companies to behave in an ethically sound and responsible way.\par \par \uc2 In Britain, the government has opened widespread opportunities for linkage between corporate social engagement and public policy programmes through initiatives such as health and education action zones and a partnership-based approach to economic and social regeneration. Such developments as these are helping to make social responsibility a core topic for debate in boardrooms.\par \par \uc2 The debate is likely to be intensified later this year when a BITC study group publishes what are claimed to be the only business-led guidelines on measuring and reporting impact on society. Armed with these, it is hoped other companies can be persuaded to move in a direction already taken by many of the award finalists.\par \par \uc2 The BITC Awards for Excellence, in association with the Financial Times, are sponsored by the Department of Trade and Industry and recommended by the British Quality Foundation. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \