ed \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 COMMENT &ANALYSIS - Men in black - Robert Corzine examines whether the oil companies were themselves partly to blame for the fuel shortages that nearly paralysed the country this week.\par \par \uc2 Big oil companies draw up contingency plans to prepare them for just about every eventuality, from natural disasters to nuclear war. Yet when a loose coalition of farmers and lorry drivers angry at the high cost of petrol turned up outside refineries and fuel storage depots throughout Britain this week, the industry seemed at a loss to know what to do.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 With the exception of BP, which made one of its senior executives available for television radio interviews, the industry remained strangely silent and aloof, apart from issuing terse communiques on how many filling stations had run out of fuel.\par \par \uc2 More curious still, it transpired that few if any of the refineries were being physically blockaded by the protesters; rather, the petrol shortages that quickly arose across the country were caused by the tanker drivers, who were seemingly unwilling to move supplies.\par \par \uc2 To some - not least the government, which was caught completely unawares by the scale of the popular revolt - the oil companies' behaviour has hinted at collusion with the protesters. Was the industry hoping to profit from any concessions the tax revolt might have won to squeeze higher margins from petrol prices?\par \par \uc2 Esso, Britain's largest petrol retailer, did little to quell such suspicions when it imposed - and then just as suddenly rescinded - an increase of 2 pence per litre of petrol on Thursday, just as the demonstrators were preparing to go home.\par \par \uc2 The oil companies strenuously deny the allegation of collusion. "Absolutely not," says Malcolm Brinded, the senior Shell executive dealing with the crisis. Instead, the industry cites safety as the main reason why its fuel tankers were pulled off the road so quickly. Although actual violence was rare, intimidation of drivers was widespread, it insists.\par \par \uc2 True enough, there were reports that some protesters told tanker drivers that they would be filmed if they tried to make deliveries and that their photographs would be posted on the internet. There were also reports that their families were threatened, and that tanker-drivers might be harassed by other lorry drivers.\par \par \uc2 Yet given the good-natured mood of much of the protest activity, these fears appear exaggerated. Some senior police officers say the oil companies did not seek firm intervention from the authorities until the crisis was well under way.\par \par \uc2 The oil companies counter they were told by some police forces that they lacked the manpower to escort the tankers to their destinations until the government acted to issue emergency orders.\par \par \uc2 There are, however, other grounds for doubting that collusion took place. The oil industry has traditionally cultivated a tough, almost military image. But the modern reality is that it is risk-averse to a degree that many outsiders would find surprising. Once a serious health and safety issue is raised, line managers have little or no discretion to do anything other than pull the tankers off the roads, say company officials. "You just can't order somebody out if they feel they are at risk," says one company official. "If there had been just one serious incident, there would have been huge legal as well as moral implications."\par \par \uc2 That innate caution was compounded by confusion within individual companies over how to respond to the sudden impact of the fuel shortages. "Nobody (in the industry) realised how fragile the system has become," says Fergus MacLeod, oil analyst as Pure Research in Edinburgh. In recent years cost-cutting has caused the companies to pare back the number of drivers and outsource many logistical functions. "The system works perfectly as long as nothing goes wrong," says Mr MacLeod, "but there is no slack in it."\par \par \uc2 Moreover, while the oil companies may have been unprepared for the crisis, one of the striking lessons of the week's events is that the industry is in no mood to take on a protest that has broad public support. There was a widespread belief within the industry that it was up to government to take a decisive role, and that it should have done so earlier in the crisis.\par \par \uc2 "In such a highly politicised situation, oil companies are very reluctant to step out in front of the politicians," admits one executive. "Were we scared that we would be standing against public opinion? Yes, although that didn't affect how we dealt with the situation."\par \par \uc2 Oil companies have in recent years worked hard to make themselves sensitive to public opinion, having suffered at the hands of consumers who disapproved of their social and environmental record. Most notably, in 1995 Shell found itself on the wrong side of an effective campaign by environmentalists throughout western Europe when it tried to dump the Brent Spar oil storage platform in the deep waters of the Atlantic ocean. Widespread protests and a sometimes violent boycott of its service stations in Germany brought home to executives just how powerful a force public opinion can be.\par \par \uc2 The oil companies have since invested heavily to portray themselves as caring and sensitive organisations at pains to keep in step with public opinion beyond their narrow business focus.\par \par \uc2 BP's recent corporate rebranding, with a new logo in the shape of a flower and the slogan "Beyond Petroleum", aligns the company with issues of broad public concern such as the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 In this context, it is not surprising that Esso should have been the company to risk outrage by attempting to increase petrol prices. Exxon, its US parent, is seen in the industry as the most conservative and traditional oil company, and the one most opposed to environmental regulation and "non-traditional activities".\par \par \uc2 Finally, if the oil companies were secretly hoping the protesters would win concessions from the government, they would have been playing a dangerous game.\par \par \uc2 In the first place, it is not clear the industry would benefit greatly from a cut in petrol taxes. Most experts believe fuel demand in Britain is generally not price-sensitive. Consumption did not increase significantly when the underlying crude oil price plummeted to under $10 a barrel at the beginning of last year, and nor has there been any sharp downturn in demand now that crude prices are above $30 a barrel.\par \par \uc2 Competition between petrol retailers and between petrol retailers and supermarkets has grown intense in recent years, with some companies such as Shell reporting that they make almost no profit from petrol sales in the UK. They rely instead on convenience stores to support their service station network.\par \par \uc2 BP says it hopes to make 1p in profit from every litre of petrol sold, compared with the 62.5p per litre that it collects for the government.\par \par \uc2 However, with crude prices at such high levels, the oil companies are reporting record profits from their upstream oil and gas production divisions. Two years ago the government was thwarted in its efforts to wrest more money from the North Sea oil fields because of the collapse in crude oil prices.\par \par \uc2 Many executives fear that if the government does agree in the next few weeks to cut fuel duties, it might look no further than the North Sea to offset the loss of revenue. The recent announcement by Shell that it intends to boost spending in the North Sea was thought to be aimed in part at heading off any new government initiative to raise offshore taxes.\par \par \uc2 "I can't see that the oil companies have gained any material benefits from this crisis," says Mr MacLeod. "All they have succeeded in doing over the past week is to draw attention to themselves and their high levels of profitability." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 bp : \uc2 BP PLC\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\as