spnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 When Americans go for their morning coffee on Wednesday, they will be able to appease their social conscience along with their thirst.\par \par \uc2 Starbucks, which runs the largest chain of coffee houses in the US, has started selling coffee guaranteed to have been grown without exploiting farmers in the poor countries that produce most of the world's coffee.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Fair Trade certified coffee - described as a "balanced light-to-medium blend with complementary acidity and body" - will sell for $11.45 a pound. That is about $1.50 more than the chain's house coffee, but several dollars less than its more exotic varieties.\par \par \uc2 The new blend of conscience and capitalism is the result of strenuous lobbying by TransFair USA, a non-profit group that provides independent certification that producers are being paid a decent wage for their products.\par \par \uc2 Paul Rice, executive director of TransFair, says the agreement with Starbucks ensures that Latin American farmers selling beans for Fair Trade coffee will receive at least $1.26 per pound under long-term contracts. That compares with recent market prices of as low as 78 cents per pound, of which the farmers are normally receiving just 20 to 30 cents after middlemen take a share, he says.\par \par \uc2 TransFair is hoping American consumers, who are widely seen as being notoriously indifferent to anything but price, will be willing to pay a small premium for the comfort of knowing that more of their money is making its way into the pockets of poor farmers.\par \par \uc2 "Fair trade is an alternative paradigm to charity," said Mr Rice. "What we're saying is pay a decent price for an excellent product, and help the farmers bootstrap their way out of poverty."\par \par \uc2 The deal with Starbucks represents the first time the fair trade movement has made serious inroads into the US mass consumer market. Until today, the fair trade label was limited to a smattering of craft shops and some coffees sold in Californian grocery stores.\par \par \uc2 By contrast, European consumers can already buy a range of food products carrying fair trade labels, including coffee, tea, chocolate, honey and most recently bananas. European sales of fair trade coffee alone were about $300m last year, and represented 7 per cent of the UK's ground coffee market.\par \par \uc2 Seattle-based Starbucks boasts 2,300 outlets, making it by far the largest premium coffee seller in the US. Gourmet coffees have captured about a third of the market, in a country where 80 per cent of adults drink coffee.\par \par \uc2 Starbucks is nearly the perfect candidate for fair trade products, says Mr Rice, who has worked with coffee co-operatives in Nicaragua that sold to Cafedirect, Britain's first fair trade brand.\par \par \uc2 "Coffee was far and away the hottest market we could plug into. It's a high-growth, high-margin business with a consumer profile nearly identical to that of socially conscious consumers," he said.\par \par \uc2 Starbucks has also tried to cultivate a reputation as an enlightened company. The deal with TransFair "demonstrates our commitment to coffee producers and their families, communities and the natural \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," said Dave Olsen, Starbucks' senior vice president, \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 It did not hurt that the company unexpectedly found itself on the wrong side of the anti-globalisation protests that rocked Seattle during the World Trade Organisation meeting last November. A Starbucks coffee house was vandalised, and the company was facing further opposition from activists, who accused it of treating poor farmers unfairly.\par \par \uc2 Mr Rice is hoping that the Starbucks deal will be the first of many. He has drawn up marketing plans for chocolate, tea, sugar and bananas, and would like to get involved in certifying clothing and footware.\par \par \uc2 "There is a groundswell of consumer interest," he said. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 sbcoff : \uc2 Starbucks Corp\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i66 : \uc2 Hotels/Restau