CK - Class act profits from industry - EDUCATION - A scheme to place teachers in industry has introduced a fresh way of thinking to schools and business, says Jim.\par \par \uc2 The ringing bell sets up an ear-shattering din in the reception area of the Rosemary Musker High School outside Thetford, Norfolk. A schoolgirl has trapped her finger in a door and is crying; another cannot decide whether or not to go home after fainting in assembly. A tall boy wants to know where he should be after losing his timetable.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Jane Still, deputy headteacher, is undismayed. She leaves these problems to her staff and leads the way to her tiny office. Ms Still is a very business-like figure - and for good reason: she is one of a small band of teachers with unique experience of British industry.\par \par \uc2 The 750 pupils change classes in the rain with little fuss as Ms Still describes her time as an HTI (Heads, Teachers &Industry) secondee to the nearby plant of Baxter Healthcare, the multinational medical equipment manufacturers. She spent a year in industry and Baxter paid her school salary.\par \par \uc2 Unlike many business-school programmes in the UK, the HTI scheme goes beyond philanthropy. "I had to work on a project to add value to the company," says Ms Still. So far, 250 HTI secondees have been placed since 1986 - 30 were placed this year.\par \par \uc2 The idea is to offer local companies a senior manager - an experienced teacher - in order to cover a specific project. In effect, according to HTI, the company gets an outsourced management consultant for 12 months for the price of hiring one for only 16 weeks.\par \par \uc2 "I think - I hope - I was working as a manager anyway. It's what I'm paid for - that and to be a good teacher," says Ms Still. She joined Baxter's human resources department and redesigned their in-house suggestions scheme. It is now known as Points Taken and staff are rewarded for good ideas with gift vouchers.\par \par \uc2 Baxter was in the process of reorganisation at its Thetford plant when Ms Still arrived and she was able to watch the new US plant manager build a fresh vision for the company. "It was the best training I ever had," she says. As well as Points Taken, she designed a new database to measure important performance indicators, and completed a communications audit.\par \par \uc2 Back at Rosemary Musker, Ms Still used some of the skills she learned in industry, although she is clear that schools are not companies. "I have never heard anyone call a child a product," she says.\par \par \uc2 Staff returning to work after more than five days' absence get a "Return To Work" interview; new teachers have to keep "Critical Incident Diaries"; parents get customer feedback surveys; middle managers receive a training needs analysis and team-building is used for select groups of managers.\par \par \uc2 The relationship between Baxter - one of Thetford's biggest employers - and the school has flourished. A mentoring scheme has helped older children to plan their careers. Baxter has also hosted numeracy training days in preparation for Key Stage 2 and 3 tests. The company's nurse visits the school regularly to check on staff cholesterol levels, while one of the school's disabled children has written an access report on the Thetford plant.\par \par \uc2 The problem is that there are few companies following Baxter's lead in the UK. Estelle Morris, the school standards' minister, recently visited US schools and returned determined to change a culture that prohibit schools from forming relationships with local companies. "I got the feeling that US companies do not think involvement in education is an optional extra."\par \par \uc2 "My message to schools would be: 'Be braver'," said Mrs Morris. "They should be confident that industry can learn from them - and needs them".\par \par \uc2 However, the UK government team of educational experts did acknowledge that the US \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  helps to foster links between schools and local businesses. First, more US companies have headquarters outside the big cities. And the US labour market is less flexible so companies rely on local schools for recruitment needs.\par \par \uc2 Anne Evans, chief executive of HTI, says although only 30 secondees have been placed this year, she could have filled 300 places. "But the gap is narrowing, even if we still have a long way to go," she says. The challenge is to widen the pool of companies prepared to get involved in educational projects. Founding companies, including Rowntrees and Reckitt &Colman, had the rare vision, she says, to see that placements would lead to a greater awareness in schools about what constitutes "employability".\par \par \uc2 To attract a wider pool of companies, Ms Evans decided to market HTI schemes as mutually beneficial: "It should be a win/win situation for both sides - it is not philanthropy," she says. Ms Evans offers companies the opportunity to have a first-class manager for a very attractive price, while the teacher - and the school - gets an inside view of what employers are looking for in future employees. "It's about much more than the curriculum - it is about thinking in an entrepreneurial way," she says. Other ideas include non-executive directorships for teachers and cross-sector mentoring.\par \par \uc2 The HTI pool now includes IBM, HSBC, Lloyds TSB and Glaxo Wellcome. "Of course, it enhances \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  - but that is a by-product. It used to be the other way round," she says.\par \par \uc2 There is evidence that the benefits are working the other way, as more companies become interested in formal links with schools. Harvard education expert Professor Rosabeth Moss Kanter says: "First, it demonstrates how competent you are. What better way to prove it than taking on and solving the great problems of society?" It also allows companies to operate in a completely different setting - an ideal place to try new ideas. And it helps with recruitment. "It's a real edge in a very tight employment market," says Ms Moss Kanter. Finally, involvement in the education system "takes you down the food chain" so companies can hire early, and get the best candidates.\par \par \uc2 Gill Richards, Human Resources manager at Baxter Healthcare in Thetford says of Ms Still's secondment: "We got a lot out of it - a very talented and skilled resource was available to us for a year on various projects".\par \par \uc2 The suggestions scheme has proved a success, says Mrs Richards. "She got to know the culture of the company and produced a high quality product at the end of the year." Baxter is now considering funding a second appointment.\par \par \uc2 Companies interested in the HTI scheme can e-mail: a.evans@hti.org.uk. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c21 : \uc2 Output/Production | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gedu : \uc2 Education\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlp