to enter third-round parliamentary elections Wednesday following second-round voting marred by violence over the weekend. \par \par \uc2  Police fired live ammunition and tear gas at voters Saturday in three northern villages, and, elsewhere, fistfights between supporters of rival candidates turned to gunfire. As night fell, four people were dead and more than 60 were injured. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  The third stage of the elections is scheduled for Nov. 8 and is to include the capital, Cairo. The new 454-seat legislature is to convene in mid-December. Ten seats are filled by presidential appointment; the rest are elected. \par \par \uc2  Results of the second-stage run-offs were expected Sunday. President Hosni Mubarak's National Democratic Party emerged from the first stage of voting, which was held last month, with 118 of the 150 seats contested. Opposition parties won four, independents endorsed by the Muslim Brotherhood won six and other independents won 20. Only 18 of the 134 seats contested in the second stage were won outright Oct. 29, nine by ruling NDP candidates and half by independents unaffiliated with the Brotherhood. \par \par \uc2  In Dakahla, 200 kilometers northeast of Cairo, police on Saturday tried to disperse voters who were angry that security forces had prevented them from casting ballots. \par \par \uc2  An 18-year-old, Hani Noaman al-Sabbouhi, died after being shot three times in the head, according to hospital officials. At least 24 other people were treated for gunshot wounds or tear-gas inhalation. \par \par \uc2  Egypt's largest Islamic group, the outlawed Muslim Brotherhood, enjoys strong support in Dakahla, and residents in some such areas have complained throughout the three-stage elections that security forces are limiting who votes. Voting Saturday was for run-off contests in the second stage of balloting and covered parts of the Nile Delta, Sinai Peninsula and southern Egypt. Word of trouble came from the Nile Delta. \par \par \uc2  "We just want our rights. Where's the freedom they are talking about?" asked Mohammed Shabaan, who said he wasn't allowed to vote in Dakahla. \par \par \uc2  In the village of Idyar, 80 kilometers north of Cairo, police clashed with supporters of the ruling National Democratic Party candidate -- an unusual occurrence. The reason for the clash, involving gunfire and tear gas, wasn't clear. (AP) \par \par \uc2  --- \par \par \uc2  Monday, Nov. 6 \par \par \uc2  EU -- The French Presidency holds a news conference in Brussels ahead of the Ecofin and \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  councils on Tuesday, education council on Thursday and development council on Friday. \par \par \uc2  GERMANY -- The EIR news agency seminar on "Hyper Inflation and World Financial Crisis," opens in Berlin. \par \par \uc2  IRAQ -- The U.N-Iraqi sanction committee is to allow Baghdad to receive oil-export payments in euros instead of dollars. \par \par \uc2  PHILIPPINES -- A House of Representatives committee is scheduled to begin considering an impeachment complaint against President Joseph Estrada, but the administration-dominated Congress is widely expected to reject the complaint. \par \par \uc2  WTO -- World Trade Organization Director-General Mike Moore speaks in London. \par \par \uc2  Tuesday, Nov. 7 \par \par \uc2  AUSTRIA -- Austrian National Bank Governor Klaus Liebscher, EBRD President Jean Lemierre and Hungarian National Bank Governor Gyorgy Suranyi will address the conference on "Completing Transition -- its Main Challenges" in Vienna. \par \par \uc2  EGYPT -- Verdicts are expected in the military trial of a prominent lawyer and 19 others charged with trying to revive a banned group that wants to transform Egypt into a country governed by Islamic laws. \par \par \uc2  EU -- Finance ministers meet in Brussels. The provisional agenda will include: European Commission report on risk capital. \par \par \uc2  GERMANY -- The state of Bavaria central bank holds a news conference in Munich, on reorganization of banks supervision in Germany. \par \par \uc2  IMF -- An International Monetary Fund team will be in Moscow to continue talks on restarting an IMF loan program that was suspended in 1998 when Russia's economy collapsed during the Asian financial crisis. \par \par \uc2  INDIA -- Former Prime Minister Narasimha Rao's appeal of his bribery conviction and three-year prison sentence will be heard by the Delhi High Court. Mr. Rao, 79 years old, who held office from 1991-96, was convicted of criminal conspiracy and corruption. \par \par \uc2  U.S. -- Americans go to the polls to pick the next U.S. president \par \par \uc2  Wednesday, Nov. 8 \par \par \uc2  AUSTRIA -- The two-day International Finance and Economic Forum opens, in Vienna, with speakers including ECB board member Sirkka Hamalainen. \par \par \uc2  CANADA -- The country's five official parties are scheduled to hold a French-language debate as part of the campaign for the Nov. 27 elections. \par \par \uc2  GERMANY -- European Central Bank Vice President Christian Noyer speaks at the state of Hesse central bank on "The Euro and the development of the European capital markets." \par \par \uc2  JORDAN -- King Abdullah II hosts a conference on promoting peace through tourism, in Amman. \par \par \uc2  PORTUGAL -- Prime Minister Antonio Guterres' Socialist party faces a cliffhanger vote on its budget in parliament, where it has exactly half of the 230 seats. \par \par \uc2  U.K. -- Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown is due to present his pre-budget report. Mr. Brown is also expected to make a statement outlining the government's response to fuel-price protests. \par \par \uc2  -- The Bank of England Monetary Policy Committee holds a two-day meeting in London and will announce its decision on interest rates on Thursday, which is expected to be unchanged. \par \par \uc2  Thursday, Nov. 9 \par \par \uc2  BELGIUM -- The European Business Network for Social Cohesion holds "First European Business Convention on Building \b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate Social\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 Responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 ." (to Nov. 10) \par \par \uc2  EU -- The European Commission is due to hold a closed-door hearing in Brussels into the multi-pronged investigation of German post office Deutsche Post. \par \par \uc2  GERMANY -- Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder joins leaders of the Jewish community and others for a demonstration against neo-Nazis on the anniversary of the infamous 1938 pogrom, or Kristallnacht, the "Night of Broken Glass." The march, also on the anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall, comes after a recent wave of hate-fueled violence in Germany against immigrants. \par \par \uc2  IEA -- The International Energy Agency releases its monthly oil market report in Paris. \par \par \uc2  OIC -- The Organization of Islamic Conference meets in Doha, Qatar. \par \par \uc2  WTO -- Oman will become the World Trade Organization's 139th member. The country opened negotiations to join the trade body in April 1996. \par \par \uc2  Friday, Nov. 10 \par \par \uc2  ARGENTINA -- The country's telecommunications sector is set to be opened to new competition. \par \par \uc2  EU -- Development ministers meet in Brussels. \par \par \uc2  GROUP OF EIGHT -- Employment ministers  of The Group of Eight meet in Turin, Italy. \par \par \uc2  ITALY -- The Trilaterial Commission holds its annual "European Meeting," in Milan, with guests including center-right opposition leader Silvio Berlusconi, Prime Minister Giuliano Amato, Foreign Affairs Minister Lamberto Dini, EU Competition Commissioner Mario Monti, French Finance Minister Laurent Fabius, EU Foreign Policy Chief Javier Solana and EU Economic and Monetary Affairs Commissioner Pedro Solbes. (to Nov. 12) \par \par \uc2  JAPAN -- The Ministry of Finance is expected to finalize the economic package. \par \par \uc2  RUSSIA -- President Vladimir Putin and Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko will sign a treaty providing for Belarus to adopt the Russian ruble as its official currency. \par \par \uc2  --- \par \par \uc2  Corporate News \par \par \uc2  Monday \par \par \uc2  Deutsche Post (Germany) -- Neuer Markt listing \par \par \uc2  Takeda Chemicals (Japan) -- First-half results \par \par \uc2  KPN  (Netherlands) -- Shares subscription period begins \par \par \uc2  OM Gruppen (Sweden) -- Extraordinary general meeting in connection with its offer for the London Stock Exchange. At the meeting, OM Gruppen's board will present a proposal for authorization to issue new shares. \par \par \uc2  British Airways (U.K.) -- Half-year results \par \par \uc2  Boots (U.K.) -- Dutch stores sale. This health-and-beauty chain store plans to sell its 17 Dutch stores and distribute its beauty- and personal-care brands there through Ahold NV's Etos unit. \par \par \uc2  Carphone Warehouse (U.K.) -- Half-year results \par \par \uc2  Cisco Systems (U.S.) -- First-quarter results \par \par \uc2  CNA Financial (U.S.) -- Third-quarter results \par \par \uc2  May Department Stores (U.S.) -- Third-quarter results \par \par \uc2  Voicestream Wireless (U.S.) -- Third-quarter results \par \par \uc2  Waste Management (U.S.) -- Third-quarter results \par \par \uc2  Tuesday \par \par \uc2  Unipetrol (Czech Rep.) -- Consolidated nine-month results. The results from this refinery and petrochemicals group should show improvement despite unfavorable developments in the Czech crown. \par \par \uc2  Ryanair (Ireland) -- Firs