spnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 In Geneva the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, which brings together more than 100 governments and hundreds of scientists and other experts, publishes the results of its latest review. The developing world is expected to suffer most from the adverse effects of global warming, including drought, floods and more frequent extreme weather events. A recent study by Munich Re, the reinsurer, put worldwide annual losses due to climate change by 2050 at more than $300bn a year.\par \par \uc2 Strong stuff\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Health and youth ministers from 51 European nations meet in Stockholm for a three-day conference on tackling the growing problem of alcohol abuse among young people. Studies to be presented to the conference, organised by the World Health Organisation and the Swedish government, which holds the European Union presidency, show binge drinking and drunkenness on the rise. This in turn is linked to violence, unsafe sex, traffic and other accidents.\par \par \uc2 Against racism\par \par \uc2 Government officials and human rights experts from Asia meet in Teheran to define their common regional position for a United Nations global conference against racism to be held in South Africa at the end of August. The draft declaration for negotiation at the three-day conference includes a controversial call for countries that pursued colonialism and slavery in the past to compensate victims. Though aimed at Japan's refusal to compensate Korean "comfort women", the implications for other rich nations would be far-reaching.\par \par \uc2 Two days in one\par \par \uc2 The US celebrates presidents' day, an amalgam of Lincoln's (February 12) and Washington's (February 22) birthdays. It has traditionally become a big day for cut-price sales as retailers clear their shelves of winter merchandise to make room for spring stock.\par \par \uc2 Cigar central\par \par \uc2 The third annual Havana cigar festival is due to start in the Cuban capital. Production is strictly regulated by the government but demand is such that there is a profitable trade in counterfeit cigars.\par \par \uc2 Unwelcome visitors\par \par \uc2 An international conference on eradicating invasive plants and animals that have colonised islands is held in Auckland, New Zealand. As well as rabbits and rats, feral cats, pigs, sheep and goats can destroy indigenous species and will be the subject of case studies (to February 23).\par \par \uc2 Holidays\par \par \uc2 Canada, Puerto Rico, US, Venezuela, Turkmenistan.\par \par \uc2 TUESDAY 20\par \par \uc2 Cybersquatters out\par \par \uc2 The World Intellectual Property Organisation holds a conference in Geneva to discuss the problem of "cybersquatting" - abusive use of someone else's trademark - on internet addresses registered at country level. Wipo already runs an online arbitration service for so-called generic top level domain names such as .com, .net and .org, and also handles disputes for some small countries with sought-after suffixes such as .tv and .nu.\par \par \uc2 Yemen referendum\par \par \uc2 Yemen holds a referendum, ordered by President Ali Abdullah Saleh, on constitutional amendments that would enable him to dissolve parliament and extend his term in office.\par \par \uc2 Combined energy\par \par \uc2 About 500 people from around the world will attend a two-day international symposium in Tokyo on energy co-operation in the Pacific region. Bijan Zanganeh, Iran's oil minister, will make a keynote speech. The participants will exchange opinions on energy security issues.\par \par \uc2 WEDNESDAY 21\par \par \uc2 Narcotics report\par \par \uc2 The Vienna-based International Narcotics Control Board publishes its annual report on implementation of the United Nations international drug control treaties. In its 1999 report the INCB focused on the lack of availability of controlled substances such as morphine to treat patients in developing countries. In the latest report it criticises the "pill-popping culture" in rich nations leading to overconsumption of psychotropic substances such as tranquilisers, sleeping pills and amphetamines.\par \par \uc2 Environmental business\par \par \uc2 A conference organised by the Business in the \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  pressure group takes place at the Commonwealth Institute in London. All aspects of sustainability as a business concern are expected to be covered, as are themes of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and climate change.\par \par \uc2 Congo conclave\par \par \uc2 A meeting of foreign ministers of African countries involved in the Congo conflict is held in New York. Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia have hundreds of troops in the country fighting for the Kabila administration, while the rebels are supported by Rwanda and Uganda.\par \par \uc2 Olympian task begins\par \par \uc2 A delegation from the International Olympic Committee Evaluation Commission starts its tour of candidate cities for the 2008 Olympics in Beijing. The other candidates are Osaka, Toronto, Istanbul and Paris.\par \par \uc2 Holidays\par \par \uc2 Mauritius, Bangladesh.\par \par \uc2 THURSDAY 22\par \par \uc2 Tourist trade\par \par \uc2 The World Trade Organisation in Geneva hosts a two-day symposium on tourism services, which are expected to be one of the areas for future liberalisation negotiations by WTO members. The aim of the symposium is to look at current developments in the $1,300bn industry and how the sector, which is of crucial importance for many developing countries, might be handled in WTO talks.\par \par \uc2 Holiday\par \par \uc2 Egypt.\par \par \uc2 FRIDAY 23\par \par \uc2 Border agreement\par \par \uc2 Boris Trajkovski and Ljubco Geogievski, president and prime minister of Macedonia, host a summit meeting of Balkan leaders in Skopje. The continuing unrest in the Presevo valley in southern Serbia, where ethnic Albanian separatists are waging an armed campaign, is expected to dominate the agenda. The summit, held every year, will be attended by the leaders of Albania, Bulgaria, Greece, Macedonia, Romania, Serbia and Turkey.\par \par \uc2 Brussels face-to-face\par \par \uc2 Colin Powell, the new US secretary of state, and Igor Ivanov, the Russian foreign minister, have their first face-to-face meeting, in Brussels. The planned US national missile defence system, fiercely opposed by Russia and China, will be among the subjects for discussion.\par \par \uc2 SATURDAY 24\par \par \uc2 Flood of interest\par \par \uc2 North and South Korea hold their first working-level talks in Pyongyang on the subject of co-operation against flood damage on the Imjin River.\par \par \uc2 Spam, spam, spam\par \par \uc2 The 11th annual World Spam Carving Contest is scheduled to be held in Seattle. Contestants have 15 minutes to create a sculpture from two small tins of Spam. Power tools are banned.\par \par \uc2 Governors meet\par \par \uc2 The US National Governor's Association meets in Washington DC.\par \par \uc2 Holiday\par \par \uc2 Estonia.\par \par \uc2 SUNDAY 25\par \par \uc2 Russo-Japanese talks\par \par \uc2 Yoshiro Mori, the Japanese prime minister, will meet Vladimir Putin, the Russian president, to discuss how they should proceed with negotiations about a bilateral peace treaty. A joint statement will be issued.\par \par \uc2 Holidays\par \par \uc2 Bolivia, Brazil. Compiled by Roger Beale Fax 44 20 7873 3196. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gciv : \uc2 Community/Civic Groups | gdip : \uc2 International Relations | gpol : \uc2 Domestic Politics\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 africa :  | africaz : \uc2 Africa | asia :  | asiaz : \uc2 Asia | ausnz : \uc2 Australia/Oceania | austr : \uc2 Australia | eur :  | eurz : \uc2 Europe | meast :  | meastz : \uc2 Middle East\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\par