r\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 INSIDE TRACK - Europe rises to social challenge - CORPORATE CITIZENSHIP - Companies must reach out to stakeholders if they are to turn CSR into good business, says Roger Cowe.\par \par \uc2 A green paper on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  (CSR) published yesterday by the European Commission looks set to stimulate the first official interest in Europe in the voluntary movement.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The green paper talks of combining profitability with sustainability and accountability and highlights the need to rationalise the plethora of codes and standards that assails any company trying to understand what social responsibility means in practice.\par \par \uc2 The document does not propose any definite steps but demonstrates the extent to which the Commission's initial concern with unemployment has spread to a wider corporate impact on society. Some say the original employment initiative has been hijacked by single-issue pressure groups but business is also pushing the wider issues, such as human rights, diversity and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 In fact, the Commission has part-financed a business organisation called CSR Europe, which last month launched a campaign to raise the sights of the Continent's business community well beyond traditional concerns for employment and labour rights. The campaign will involve a 10-nation roadshow, beginning in Athens in December and culminating in what is described as a "CSR Olympics", involving awards for best practice as part of a European Year on CSR in 2004. Separate strands aim to boost the teaching of "responsible management" in business schools and to enhance the growth of socially responsible investment (SRI) funds.\par \par \uc2 The organisation wants companies to pay more attention to diversity, human rights and social and environmental issues. It also wants companies to measure and report their progress.\par \par \uc2 CSR Europe is led by Etienne Davignon, a European Union veteran and until recently chairman of Belgium's Societe Generale. Launching the campaign at a conference in Copenhagen at the end of last month, Viscount Davignon dismissed free-market critics who accuse CSR of being anti-capitalist and anti-market.\par \par \uc2 "There is no contradiction in the term '\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 '. The market system is the system we have to work with. But it must be a human system and there are imperfections. We want to keep the benefits and get rid of the shortcomings."\par \par \uc2 The former EU commissioner also has his critics on the left. His organisation is seen by some as "camouflage", allowing big business to claim responsibility without doing anything more than paying its subscriptions. And trade unionists worry that voluntarism cannot provide sufficient protection for workers.\par \par \uc2 So far, CSR Europe has nearly 50 members, mostly multinationals. Part of its campaign is to spread the word to smaller businesses. For now, members include the likes of Nike, Shell and BP, which have been stung into action by crises over specific issues, as well as those such as International Business Machines and Levi's that have longstanding traditions of social awareness. But there is also a growing number of companies that believe that while social responsibility is much more than philanthropy, it is about money, not morals. They include Kingfisher from the UK, Telecom Italia, ABB and Accor.\par \par \uc2 In this respect it is akin to the quality movement - doing business better as a means of doing better business. John Steele, group personnel director of British Telecommunications, brings it down to earth: "It is about doing business in a way that persuades our customers to buy from us, our employees to work hard for us and our communities to accept us," he says.\par \par \uc2 If only it were as simple as that. CSR has many different strands, means different things in different parts of Europe and faces several challenges in spite of the growing backing in official circles.\par \par \uc2 So far, developments have been driven largely by campaign groups such as Greenpeace, Amnesty and Oxfam. Their concerns with pollution, human rights and poverty have created what Simon Zadek calls a "cross-sector virus" that has spread from textiles, through energy and mining companies and this year hit the pharmaceuticals industry, which was forced to back down from its patent action in the South African courts.\par \par \uc2 Mr Zadek is chairman of the UK-based Institute of Social and Ethical Accountability. "This virus will go on through different sectors and different countries in Europe," he predicts. But he sees two other contrasting drivers as well - competition and regulation - and believes the three could be mutually reinforcing.\par \par \uc2 Competition will work if employees really shy away from companies with poor records and if consumers put their money where their mouths are when it comes to "ethical" consumption.\par \par \uc2 But regulation, in the form of EU intervention, could be more problematic. Julia Cleverdon, head of the UK group Business in the Community, says voluntarism has been crucial to progress so far. "The last thing we want is an EU directive on CSR," says Ms Cleverdon. "The lesson from the UK experience is clear. What makes CSR successful here is the growing realisation by companies that they derive real business benefit from it. Anyone pushed into CSR will do the bare minimum, pay lip service and duck out of it at the earliest opportunity."\par \par \uc2 Any attempt at heavy-handed intervention from the Commission would almost certainly be the kiss of death for CSR among European companies. But there are moves short of that which could encourage greater responsibility and transparency - and these will be pushed by the incoming Belgian presidency. They include adopting two UK innovations: the requirement for pension trustees to make an annual statement on their social, ethical and environmental policy and the move towards social and environmental reporting, which is likely to be included in the new Companies Act.\par \par \uc2 The Belgians are also very keen on "social labelling", which is equivalent to the ecolabel scheme that would give shoppers assurance as to the labour standards behind the products they buy.\par \par \uc2 Given the failure of ecolabelling to capture the public's interest, the prospects for social labels may be slim. But, as Mr Zadek says, CSR will drift into shallow public relations unless it means something to consumers, employees or other stakeholders.\par \par \uc2 "If CSR can't generate connections, it won't work," he says. "Somewhere it has to generate a response." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertal