0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  (Copyright (c) 2001, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.)   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  It is August and the few bureaucrats left in Brussels are hard at work on something called the "\b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  Summit." This buzzword -- and this summit -- could eventually cost shareholders a lot of money.   \par \par \uc2  The meeting of EU leaders, which is still in the planning stages, is part of a long-running effort to codify the demands of activist groups that want businesses to pay for everything from preserving "old growth" forests to improving the lives of cocoa-bean farm workers in Sierra Leone.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  "\b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 " is a catch-all term for a left-wing agenda. Pick environmental restoration, literacy training or any other cause from the 1960s, and you can bet that activists want your company to help ease the problem -- to improve your "social reputation" of course. Too bad that this agenda has nothing to do with making products and selling services.   \par \par \uc2  Some European companies are already falling in line. Unilever, British Telecom and the Royal Dutch/Shell Group of Companies are bragging about their "socially responsible" deeds in glossy reports. British Petroleum, one of the world's biggest producers of oil and natural gas, now says that BP stands for "Beyond Petroleum." A recent report on British Telecom, the former U.K. phone monopoly, is quite telling: "Social reputation has a direct effect on customer loyalty and on turnover. If that effect could be quantified at just 1% [of turnover], BT's latest community initiative would have won them GBP 150 million [$217 million]."   \par \par \uc2  Note the magical realist language here: If the effect could be quantified, it would be worth GBP 150 million. Even the 1% figure seems to have been picked at random -- why not 0.1% or 10%?   \par \par \uc2  Certainly "social responsibility" doesn't automatically boost shareholder value. Remember those "socially responsible mutual funds" that invested in only the most politically correct companies? Only 9% of socially responsible funds beat the S&P 500 over the past decade. So, why is business still supporting this nonsense?   \par \par \uc2  There are a variety of reasons, according to those active in the field. Some see it a publicity ploy. "This is mostly a PR exercise," says Julian Morris, a director of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and technology program at London's Institute for Economic Affairs. "They are doing things that look good, that are telegenic. That kind of spending has a dubious effect on the bottom line."   \par \par \uc2  Some managers say that it amounts to a "peace treaty" with would-be demonstrators. After the riots in Seattle, Goteborg and Genoa, there may be even more of these projects undertaken by companies -- and even some activists hired. "Often these protesters don't know what it is they want," says Bill Shireman, a lobbyist, and CEO of Global Futures, a San Francisco and Tokyo-based consulting firm that works extensively in the \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social\b0 \highlight\uc2 -\b \highlight22\uc2 responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  realm. "But getting them at the table with executives can help them figure out what they want."   \par \par \uc2  Mr. Shireman recalls a deal he helped broker. Protesters were locking themselves inside automobiles at new-car shows and issuing nasty press releases to target Mitsubishi Corp. Never mind that they didn't have issues with the car maker itself. What they were really upset about was a supplier to a sister company, Mitsubishi Trading Group that was felling trees in "old-growth" forests. After a raft of bad publicity, Mitsubishi executives met with the radicals and persuaded their sister company to harvest lumber from different forests. "We're going to see more deals like this in the future," predicts Mr. Shireman.   \par \par \uc2  Some firms hope to buy protection from the government itself, notes Joseph Ramano, a senior manager at High Ground, Inc., a marketing consulting firm. "There are lots of politicians who will make noise about companies like KFC or McDonald's if they don't buy their meat or chicken locally, use local wrapping-paper suppliers, and hire only local workers," says Mr. Romano, who recently completed a master's thesis on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  at Boston University. "It's protectionism in disguise. And if they don't comply, a competitor will. It's also a way to look concerned and active for the government, when their spending regimes are constrained."   \par \par \uc2  Faced with strict EU-mandated budget guidelines, rising welfare-state costs and increasing global competition, European governments are not able to meet activists' demands -- so they want business to do it. "This is what I call the transfer philosophy," says Diana Shayon, the chief executive officer of HRN Consulting, a Philadelphia-based brand-management firm that works with an array of European companies. "It's the government and nonprofit groups making corporations pick up the things that they aren't going to do anymore."   \par \par \uc2  To be sure, some of these projects make business sense. Georges Auguste, environmental director of Geneva-based ST Microelectronics, cites a water-conservation program that cut company water expenses $9 million over the past seven years. A concurrent energy-conservation project also reduced expenses. All told, "We have saved something like $40 million dollars," says Mr. Auguste.   \par \par \uc2  But most "socially responsible" projects don't fit this pattern -- if they did, companies would gladly do them without prodding. And, unlike the savings at ST Microelectronics, which can be measured using standard accounting practices, most socially responsible initiatives have no measurable bottom-line benefit.   \par \par \uc2  If companies want to legitimately spend investors' money in this area, new business metrics will have to be developed to track the benefits of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , says Eric Israel, a partner in KPMG's Amsterdam office. "One outstanding question is whether stakeholders and other users, from banks and investors to employees and local communities, can rely on the information and data presented in environmental reports in order to use these in their decision making," Mr. Israel tells me. Creating new reliable statistics will allow managers to see which "responsible" measures really enhance shareholder value.   \par \par \uc2  But don't expect the EU to be this rational. In June, the EU published a "green paper" called "Promoting a European Framework for \b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 " that stressed that firms should go beyond "legal compliance" and invest "more into human capital, the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the relations with stakeholders."   \par \par \uc2  The EU seems to be looking to persuade companies to become community activists. Julie Garman, a strategist with Global Policy Consultants, a Brussels-based firm that tracks EU policy, expects that the EU will come out with a strongly worded framework for all companies operating in Europe.   \par \par \uc2  In the 1990s, executives lavished money on corporate jets and fancy offices -- until shareholders revolted. Now executives want to spend money to ease their consciences and soothe their foes. Will history repeat itself?   \par \par \uc2  ---   \par \par \uc2  Mr. Koprowski is a journalist who has covered business for 16 years in Europe, Asia and the U.S.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 btcom : \uc2 BT Group PLC\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctl