\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 INSIDE TRACK - Guardians of the planet - ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTANCY - Globalisation is both increasing work for environmental advisers and changing their own organisations, says Roger Cowe.\par \par \uc2 Critics ofglobalisation argue that it is helping to destroy the planet, as businesses pollute and threaten local communities and natural resources. The growing sensitivity to environmental issues is increasingly leading companies to turn to specialist advisers.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 "People are looking for less damaging products, so the environmental issue is difficult even if there are no regulatory issues," says Robin Bidwell, chairman of ERM, one of the largest environmental consultancies. "In the past it was a matter of meeting regulations. Now you need to see how the market is going to change."\par \par \uc2 ERM has 120 offices in 34 countries; its 2,500 professional staff advise on and carry out environmental audits, site clean-ups, risk assessments and strategic reviews - increasingly on social as well as environmental issues.\par \par \uc2 Echoing the moves of its customers, ERM is also becoming more global.\par \par \uc2 The firm was formed from a UK and US consultancy, each founded during the early years of modern environmentalism in the 1970s. As in many multinationals, the two sides remained slightly separate - but that began to change this year when 3i, the UK venture capital company, invested #55m ( $81m) to buy out some of the partners and provide the capital for a globalising push. ERM is now heading for an initial public offering.\par \par \uc2 Mr Bidwell, who was one of the founders of the UK branch, says clients want a global environmental consultancy just as they want global accountancy firms and advertising agencies. That means having a unified approach, rather than more offices, although there are gaps in the network that need to be filled.\par \par \uc2 "Companies operate on a global level. They shouldn't notice where the lines are in our organisation," Mr Bidwell says.\par \par \uc2 The teeth of a recession may not be the best time to be setting out on his own globalising path but, he says: "There is huge unmet demand. We have to accept that environmental spending is often discretionary - and in a recession that gets tightened. But most companies are too far down the road to go back. Expectations have changed. After all, we don't send children up chimneys, even in a recession."\par \par \uc2 The demand that is waiting to be satisfied is a combination of new kinds of work for the corporate leaders, plus work for the laggards who are struggling to catch up. Both are being driven partly by continuing legislation and European directives and partly by new expectations and pressures.\par \par \uc2 Mr Bidwell says environmental managers need to be more strategic, to have a good grasp of wider business issues. He cites the head of \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  at a European car company as a typical example. This person, filling what had previously been a fairly technical post, now has to comment on issues about cars that will not even be produced for five years.\par \par \uc2 "The only way I can do that is to paint scenarios and show the business consequences. I have to turn it into money and focus on the cost of getting it wrong," the car manager said at a recent ERM meeting.\par \par \uc2 Not everyone is at such an advanced stage, however. Malcolm Hutton, ERM's UK managing director, reports a recent conversation with a client who was not aware of one of the EU's most controversial new regulations - the directive on end-of-life electronic and electrical equipment (called WEEE).\par \par \uc2 "Some companies feel they have dealt with the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  but it is surprising the lack of attention some are paying to developments such as WEEE. They just seem to have taken their eyes off the ball," Mr Hutton says. "Within certain sectors companies are doing very little - then they are surprised when something hits them."\par \par \uc2 He extends this criticism even to those who have kept up with regulations but have not gone further to understand risks and wider issues in \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . "Just because you are complying with regulations it doesn't mean you are reducing the level of risk to an acceptable level," Mr Hutton says.\par \par \uc2 He also identifies disconnections between head office policymakers and people on the ground, often in far-flung corners of the corporate empire, which are little understood back in the centre. He cites one manager in an Asian country who was faced with a head office prescription for responsible waste disposal. The manager worked in an \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  where it was a struggle to find anybody to take away rubbish, let alone obey detailed instructions for how to manage waste disposal. But then globalisation is supposed to be about raising environmental standards in such countries. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | genv : \uc2 Environmental News | gglblz : \uc2 Globalization | gglobe : \uc2 Global/World Issues\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 eurz : \uc2 Europe | uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IPC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Pollution &Waste | Environment | Conservation\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \