mes Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 BUSINESS &THE \b \highlight22\uc2 ENVIRONMENT\b0 \highlight\uc2  4 - Schemes failing to put money on their morals - ETHICAL INVESTMENT by Adam Courtenay - While the retail side of socially responsible investment is booming, risk-averse European corporate pensions do not offer employees ethical options already commonplace in the US.\par \par \uc2 Corporate pension trustees have never had a history of espousing radical ideas, nor of concern for social and environmental issues. Even last year, when every UK pension scheme trustee was asked by government decree to disclose "the extent to which social, environmental, or ethical considerations are taken into account in the selection, retention and realisation of investments", there was, by their own admission, very little industrial 'reconsideration'.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 A survey late last year by FT Mandate, which specialises in institutional fund mandates, found that few pension funds offer staff an ethical option, although around 30 per cent claimed to be "engaged" with some of the corporations in which they invest.\par \par \uc2 FT Mandate asked 30 major UK pension funds several basic questions - what is your stance on ethical investment? Would you consider a purely ethical mandate? How do you know the underlying investments of the fund are not invested in arms manufacturers, alcohol, tobacco or other 'ethically-challenged' organisations'?\par \par \uc2 In a pensions industry where there is huge pressure to earn even a few extra percentage points above benchmarks, there is little will to adopt ethical mandates, where screening of socially irresponsible corporations is actively employed. The most common response from the investment heads of pension funds is that the underlying investment managers - not themselves - must take responsibility.\par \par \uc2 Where exclusion was a factor, it is based on profitability, not morality: "If analysts all agree that profits are bad at tobacco firms because of paying out lawsuits to US states, then obviously that's a bad investment," said one respondent in charge of a multi-billion pound pension fund. "But we have no moral stance and see no point in putting money aside for ethical reasons in themselves."\par \par \uc2 While socially responsible investment (SRI) has experienced enormous growth among retail investors and strong interest among local council pension schemes, nearly all analysts agree that institutions, including pensions, are still wary. It was the arrival this year of the FTSE4Good index, the first UK ranking of corporates according to ethical, \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social criteria, which made corporate Britain's investor relations departments pay greater attention.\par \par \uc2 "These rankings are in their infancy," says Matt Haddon, a principal consultant at ERM Consulting Services, which specialises in \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . "Their ability to ask really deep questions about performance that you might expect from a financial credit rating agency hasn't happened yet."\par \par \uc2 Toby Belsom, an analyst at Morley Fund Management, agrees: "There are various difficulties in using indices as proof of commitment; but there needs to be more research into the relationship between sustainability and profitability."\par \par \uc2 However, the index may have created the beginnings of a kind of corporate image indicator, and those who drop out of the index may suffer reputational damage. "The chief executive, the finance officer and the investor relations people are now getting much more closely interested in the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social questions," he says. "The pressure that's coming from outside companies is forcing new channels of communication within them."\par \par \uc2 By contrast in the US, the Washington-based Social Investment Forum reported in October 1999 in its Trends Report that one out of eight dollars under professional management in the US was part of a socially responsible portfolio.\par \par \uc2 The survey found that around $2.16trn was being managed by major investing institutions (including pension funds, mutual funds, foundations and charitable/ religious institutions), accounting for 13 per cent of the $16.3trn in investment assets under management in the US.\par \par \uc2 Steven Lydenberg, research director at Kinder, Lydenberg, Domini - which screens assets for the Domini Social Investments company - says there is a growing number of company pension funds in the US which offer social choice in their defined contribution plans.\par \par \uc2 "But there is, admittedly, very little happening in the defined benefits side, where companies have control over the assets," says Mr Lydenberg.\par \par \uc2 Mr Belsom at Morley Fund Management, which runs the NPI Global Care range of funds in the UK, says UK and continental pension funds need to be able to make a business decision about risk before they will make the investments: "When this happens they will incorporate social and environmental concerns on to the corporate governance agenda."\par \par \uc2 Mr Belsom says most continental funds have been traditionally even more conservative than their UK counterparts, and only now are they beginning to "dip their toes in the water". "It's quite exciting - the big Dutch pension schemes are rapidly playing catch-up," he says.\par \par \uc2 Superior performance has long been the hallmark of ethical and SRI retail funds and one of the drivers of the industry's success. However, many SRI funds have been heavily dominated by technology as new and cleaner technologies are a strong catchment area for investment.\par \par \uc2 In the past 18 months, this technology focus has come back to haunt the SRI sector. A five-year performance comparison between SRI and UK unit trusts shows that the two sectors are now almost on a par.\par \par \uc2 Evy Hambro, the co-manager of the Merrill Lynch New Energy Technology Investment Trust, says his fund has performed poorly since its inception in October 2000. The fund is not an ethical or SRI fund - but places the bulk of assets into renewable energy projects and businesses.\par \par \uc2 "We've been hit as hard as the technology sector as a whole," says Mr Hambro. "But what we have seen is that a lot of our companies which are in the Nasdaq or the Neuer Markt have been losing significantly less than the indices as a whole."\par \par \uc2 Will the UK follow the example of the US? Government directives asking corporates to state their case are one thing, shareholder advocacy is another. Not until pension schemes become more interested - using both screening and shareholder advocacy to encourage corporate responsibility - will UK pensions change their stance.\par \par \uc2 As one investment head of a #3bn pension fund says: "It's just not appropriate at the moment." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl