 Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 BUSINESS EDUCATION - Now is the time to clarify true meaning - \b \highlight22\uc2 CORPORATE SOCIAL RESPONSIBILITY\b0 \highlight\uc2  by Sarah Murray - The interpretation of CSR varies from one business college to another and from country to country. Some good, early research may avoid misunderstandings and disappointments.\par \par \uc2 Potential MBA students looking for a programme that includes \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  (CSR) might be forgiven for being a little confused.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 While growing numbers of business school brochures broadcast prowess in teaching responsible business, definitions of what that means remain hazy, and the integration of social and environmental management into core elements of the MBA programme varies widely from school to school.\par \par \uc2 Part of the problem lies in defining \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Interpretations range from volunteering activities and involvement with non-profit organisations to teaching social and environmental management as part of core MBA topics, such as accounting, marketing and finance.\par \par \uc2 In the US, with its strong tradition of philanthropy, CSR is often interpreted as simply "giving back" rather than looking more deeply at the impact of business decisions on society and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . In the worst cases, commitment to CSR remains little more than words on a business school's prospectus. Even if a course may have once existed, if it was an add-on or an elective taught by an adjunct, it can often disappear when that particular academic has moved on.\par \par \uc2 Judith Samuelson, executive director of the Aspen Institute's Initiative for Social Innovation through Business - an organisation that monitors how well busi ness schools are integrating CSR into their courses - advises applicants to do some careful research before choosing a school.\par \par \uc2 "On a practical level, you have got to make sure (CSR) is actually being taught, and it's not just appearing in the catalogue," she says. "Look at who is teaching it and whether it's being taught by an adjunct, which would not reflect the integration of this thinking into the broader offerings."\par \par \uc2 For many schools, the emphasis is on corporate citizenship activities and social consciousness. A new Initiative for Corporate Citizenship at the Tuck School of Business at Dartmouth in the US, for example, includes setting up links with non-profit organisations and offering related summer internships. In addition, scholars and practitioners from the non-profit sector will spend time at Tuck doing research and interacting with students.\par \par \uc2 However, Paul Danos, Tuck's dean, stresses that the school is not simply creating a department for non-profit. "Tuck is not going to be a school of volunteering," he says. "(CSR) is an important outlet for students' experiences and we are blending it in with the main courses - the most fundamental thing is that we are creating materials that will be integrated into other courses."\par \par \uc2 This integrated approach, says Ms Samuelson, is crucial if CSR is to take root in business education. "If this is going to be taken seriously, it's got to be part of the core offerings of the school - like strategy, accounting and finance - and of how you think about the impact of your business processes. That's the hundred million dollar question."\par \par \uc2 Jim Copeland, CEO of accountants Deloitte &Touche, agrees. "The way to make this effective in colleges and universities is to get back to the issue of managers having responsibility for influencing the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  of the market they work in - as well as managing the enterprise," he says. "Most people do not come out of schools thinking about anything other than managing the enterprise."\par \par \uc2 One US school that has been taking this idea seriously is Kenan-Flagler at the University of North Carolina. Stuart Hart, director of the Sustainable Enterprise Initiative at the school, says the principles of CSR should be embedded in the teaching of traditional MBA subjects.\par \par \uc2 Professor Hart, who previously helped establish the corporate environmental management programme at the University of Michigan, believes Kenan-Flagler's success in this area lies in the way the school's coursework was adapted to incorporate CSR.\par \par \uc2 "We were able to move some substantial content about his stuff into selected core courses - and there are 10 to 12 faculty in the school that have strong prior knowledge and interest in this, or are actively doing work in sustainable enterprise, but who come from operations, marketing, international business or strategy perspectives."\par \par \uc2 But however embedded CSR becomes in MBA programmes, until recruiters start to demand the skills acquired by graduates of institutions, such as Michigan and Kenan-Flagler, this approach will only ever be taken up by a handful of schools.\par \par \uc2 "How to be more valuable to employers ... that's the link that allows this to work," says Mr Copeland. "Until colleges and universities realise this, and say that it's not about whether graduates are thought of as green, but whether they have given them a new way to add value to the enterprises they join, they are missing the point."\par \par \uc2 In an attempt to supply this link, six European business schools that are leaders in CSR teaching - Ashridge Management College and Cranfield School of Management in the UK, Insead in Paris, Esade in Barcelona, Copenhagen Business School and the Bruges-based College of Europe - are participating in the creation of the CSR Academy, which aims to help teaching faculty to build CSR into mainstream business education.\par \par \uc2 Although the idea of the society's needs being met by partnerships between government and business is more established in Europe than in the US, Andrew Wilson, director of Ashridge's Centre for Business and Society, believes there is still a missing link when it comes to graduate recruitment.\par \par \uc2 "Businesses are aware that they need a sophisticated approach to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Business schools see that and want to respond but say that business managers are not demanding it and recruiters are not asking about it," he says.\par \par \uc2 By presenting the business case for responsible business through a research programme, the CSR Academy aims not only to encourage business schools to develop their teaching in this area but also to encourage businesses to demand this kind of teaching from schools.\par \par \uc2 For Mr Copeland, this is the only way forward. "The acid test is whether employers will pay more to the graduates of (universities integrating CSR into their offerings) than other universities," he says. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gedu : \uc2 Education\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 eurz : \uc2 Europe | fra : \uc2 France | medz : \uc2 Mediterranean | namz : \uc2 North America | uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | usa : \uc2 United States | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IPC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Society &Social Affairs | Strategy | Education &Training | Company News | United States of America | France | United Kingdom\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr