served \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 INSIDE TRACK - Coping with a more influential role - NON-GOVERNMENTAL ORGANISATIONS - The higher profile of pressure groups is demanding greater accountability, says Alison Maitland.\par \par \uc2 Charities and other "non-governmental organisations" appear to be riding high. Activists demanding global economic justice are regaining the momentum lost after September 11. Companies are increasingly seeking NGOs' advice on environmental, social or supply chain strategies. The public, in Europe at least, trusts them far more than it trusts governments, companies or the media.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Yet this high profile raises difficult questions for NGOs. Like their campaign targets, they now face pressure for greater accountability. Are they the legitimate voice of the poor and disadvantaged? How effective are they? If they are hired to advise companies or to deliver welfare services on behalf of governments, what happens to their role as independent watchdogs?\par \par \uc2 The climate for campaigning is likely to become much tougher, says Ed Mayo, executive director of the New Economics Foundation, a radical think-tank, and a founder of the Jubilee 2000 movement for cancellation of poor countries' debts. "Low standards and lazy thinking can compromise the chances of really making a difference," he says. "Legitimacy is the heart of effective NGO operations: erode it or remove it and the NGO is left stranded, like a business facing overnight market collapse."\par \par \uc2 With these challenges in mind, Ashridge business school and the National Council for Voluntary Organisations recently asked 124 of the UK's largest charities how influential they thought they were, what demands they faced for accountability and how they viewed the balance between providing services and campaigning*. The respondents, including international organisations such as Friends of the Earth, Save the Children and WWF, the conservation group, all had a turnover of more than #1m a year.\par \par \uc2 One finding is that charities think they should be campaigning more. Nearly two-thirds say they are mainly or exclusively service providers but only a quarter see this as ideal. While 25 per cent say they have an even balance between service provision and campaigning, 57 per cent aspire to achieve this.\par \par \uc2 Charities involved in housing and disability are particularly keen to shift more work to campaigning. Overseas aid and famine relief bodies, which have traditionally combined advocacy with services, feel least need to change the balance.\par \par \uc2 What can companies expect from an increase in NGO campaigning? Andrew Laurence and Ian Hagg of Hill and Knowlton, the public relations company, say campaigns may shift to local issues such as training, housing and disability. "This could be particularly significant for UK companies, as many are now attempting to interpret their roles as corporate citizens, distinct from global leaders such as BP and Shell, and often the quickest and most easily understood way for them to do this is through local initiatives." They argue that companies should seize the opportunity to emulate counterparts in other European Union countries by working with voluntary organisations and the public sector to tackle social inequities.\par \par \uc2 This may be easier said than done. The survey also reveals a gulf between NGOs and the private sector. Only 36 per cent feel they have had "a reasonable amount" or "a great deal" of success in influencing companies, while 45 per cent say they have very little success.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, companies are low down the charities' list of targets to influence. More important are the government, the public and the media. Only 26 per cent rate influencing companies as "very important". They also experience fewer demands for accountability from the private sector than from their members, the government, the media and the public.\par \par \uc2 "Companies don't want to be seen to criticise them," says Chris Gribben, co-author of the report and associate director at Ashridge Centre for Business and Society. "They often come out of confrontations with NGOs badly." No companies were prepared to sponsor the research in case it proved critical of voluntary organisations.\par \par \uc2 Charities may regard companies as relatively unimportant, partly because they receive only a tiny proportion of their income from the private sector. But NGOs can also find it hard to get access to business, despite all the talk about embracing stakeholders, says Mr Gribben. "I think there's been some change - but \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  is still pretty new for companies." Indirect influence, via the media and public opinion, emerges as far more important. The survey shows charities have generally high expectations about their future impact but they are more optimistic about influencing the public, the government and the media than companies.\par \par \uc2 Relying on the media may be problematic, however. Certainly, the media have the biggest influence on public and political thinking about \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and sustainable develop-ment, according to a recent report by SustainAbility, a think-tank, Ketchum, a public relations company, and the United Nations \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  Programme. But the report argues that media organisations lack accountability and that journalists overlook broader trends in favour of immediate dramas such as the destruction of genetically modified crops.\par \par \uc2 Media treatment of NGOs tends to be benign but that could change. Scrutiny of voluntary organisations will increase if they become more closely involved with government in delivering public services, says Alan Pike, former social affairs correspondent for the Financial Times, who is writing a book on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . In a commentary on the Ashridge/NCVO research, he says that, although only a few charities have suffered serious attacks on their reputation, the main perpetrators have been the media and other voluntary bodies.\par \par \uc2 If NGOs are to be influential and effective, Mr Mayo says, they must become more professional in research and marketing, adopt accountability standards and use technology to allow the people they represent to speak for themselves. This will cost money but should be seen as an investment: greater accountability should help to raise more funds. "Campaigning is good for society," he says, "but what constitutes good campaigning is now up for change."\par \par \uc2 * The Third Sector: Vision for the Future, #10. Hamilton House. Available from March 1. Tel: 01536 399016. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx936