ed \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 INSIDE TRACK BUSINESS EDUCATION - An energiser with big ideas - INTERVIEW ROBERT DOLAN, UNIVERSITY OF MICHIGAN - The new dean of the university's business school will bring to bear the experience he has gained at Harvard, says Della Bradshaw.\par \par \uc2 It is hard to imagine a more difficult time for a first-time dean to start at a business school than last autumn. Even before the events of September 11, departing students - both MBAs and undergraduates - were finding it tough to get jobs and executive education revenues were plummeting.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Robert Dolan, incoming dean of the University of Michigan Business School, had to follow in the footsteps of the extraordinarily successful and charismatic Joe White. What made it even more difficult for him was that he was not an internal promotion. Indeed, the former Harvard marketing professor was not even in the US when his appointment was announced; he was on a six-month teaching term at Iese business school in Spain.\par \par \uc2 Prof Dolan's first contact with the Michigan constituencies was by e-mail and his first face-to-face contact with his faculty was at the meeting on September 7. Four days later, when the "community fractured", as he puts it, "I didn't have my baseline read on where the community was".\par \par \uc2 A tough test - but, by all faculty accounts, one that he passed with flying colours. On September 11, after the terrorist attacks on New York and Washington, he called Jane Dutton, professor of business administration and associate professor of psychology, and an expert in the integration of business with personal issues, and asked her to help the faculty and staff at Michigan through the crisis.\par \par \uc2 Her presentation to them was on September 12, swiftly followed by dissemination of information to friends of the school and then to other parts of the university. A website was developed shortly afterwards.\par \par \uc2 Such responsiveness earned him high marks within the school. But, softly spoken and affable, he gives the credit to his faculty. "That's not incremental stuff - that's people just bursting out and going places. We've got to be bold and venturesome."\par \par \uc2 Prof Dolan joined Harvard in 1980 after four years teaching at the University of Chicago. He says Michigan fuses the best of both those top-drawer business schools. "The faculty are driven by management training - but with rigour. At Harvard we lived and breathed teaching. Here people teach differently but the devotion is similar."\par \par \uc2 He believes Michigan can learn from Harvard, in three ways in particular.\par \par \uc2 First, Harvard professors take it upon themselves to act as mentors to the newly recruited professors, to ensure a seamless succession.\par \par \uc2 Second, Harvard has an unrivalled set of contacts and relationships with alumni, which opens doors and helps faculty get out into the field. "That allows the problems in the field to help drive the research."\par \par \uc2 Third is the scope of Harvard's research. "If you had a really great idea ... and (it) involved four other faculty and two PhD students, you went to a senior associate dean. The mentality of the faculty was that if you had a big idea, a good idea, you could do that kind of stuff."\par \par \uc2 At Michigan, Prof Dolan hopes to alter the way research is funded to include such big schemes. He acknowledges, though, that such schemes are much easier for Harvard to implement because it has a lot more cash.\par \par \uc2 Funding for research and faculty positions is one of the biggest issues at public universities such as Michigan. Prof Dolan says one question he had was the extent to which the finances of the school would be decided by the university and to which decision-making would be taken at university level. Happily the university is fairly decentralised, he says, with revenues earned by the business school being spent there. "It means I don't have to be my persuasive best every day," he smiles.\par \par \uc2 Michigan has not, he says, lost any faculty member through being unable to pay the salary. "Overall, I'm convinced we can be competitive for the best people. The alumni support is terrific." Nonetheless, he is well aware that his best faculty are continually being approached by other business schools.\par \par \uc2 "It has struck me how fragile any institution like this is. Faculty are free agents and there is no shortage of people who know they are terrific. You just hope you can create an \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  where they (the faculty) are continually energised."\par \par \uc2 In the university town of Ann Arbor, he says, location is all - and the business school and the university should do more to promote that. "The attractiveness of this place is whether or not you like Ann Arbor," he says.\par \par \uc2 Reflecting on his own appointment, he says he never had any explicit thoughts about being a dean until he was approached. He had intended to return to Harvard to be senior associate dean and head of research after his Spanish sojourn. "The chance to impact research at Harvard was a fantastic opportunity," he says. But be believes there are bigger opportunities at Michigan.\par \par \uc2 Prof Dolan has set himself three priorities. One is to develop interdisciplinary courses with other departments in the university - the medical school, for example. A second is to focus on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , something many business schools are now exploring but that faculty at Michigan are particularly well placed to deliver.\par \par \uc2 The third - lifelong learning - has already become a mantra for the staff and faculty at Michigan. Technology is enabling the school to have a continuing relationship with alumni, but not everything needs to be high-technology. An MBA update programme is also on the agenda.\par \par \uc2 "When a University of Michigan (graduate) has a substantive problem, they should come back to the University of Michigan," he argues. "There should be a continuing intellectual relationship."\par \par \uc2 Executive education may have to change to deal with this sort of relationship, he believes. "Maybe courses should be shorter, maybe we should teach different things. Should we do more on teaching how to learn? We need to be more creative, if you believe what you teach today won't last."\par \par \uc2 Traditionally, Michigan has been one of the largest suppliers of executive education courses in the US. This is how the school earns about 25 per cent of its revenues. The new dean describes it as a "great operation".\par \par \uc2 The honeymoon over, there is one area where Prof Dolan could face resistance from faculty, however, and that is to do with overseas alliances. During Prof White's reign, Michigan was reluctant to work with other business schools, in order to retain control of the quality of the product sold under its name. However, it did run open enrolment courses jointly with other schools, such as Iese in Barcelona.\par \par \uc2 Prof Dolan is more expansionist. "Should we have a presence in western Europe? It seems to me, yes." So, will Michigan extend its collaboration with Iese? Prof Dolan hedges his bets. "It's a question worth asking ..." Faculty may not have to wait long for the answer.\par \par \uc2 This is the 13th in a series of interviews with deans from leading business schools. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gcat : \uc2 Political/General News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 namz : \uc2 North America | usa : \uc2 United States\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IPC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnu