\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2002 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Julia Cleverdon recalls with exasperation the words of an oil company chief after a harrowing visit by business leaders to a Bristol estate where drug dealers roamed freely and a 12-year-old died injecting herself on a rubbish dump.\par \par \uc2 "We'd been talking to this girl's mother, who was very powerful. We had all been absolutely caught by this woman," says Ms Cleverdon, chief executive of Business in the Community (BITC), the \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  charity. "Then this chief executive said: I tell you what I'd do. I'd torch the place. That would make the rats run."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The incident illustrates the struggle that the business-led charity, founded after riots shook Britain's inner cities in 1981, has had in persuading companies they should play a role in combating deprivation and building stable communities.\par \par \uc2 On the face of it, the persistence of the BITC team, together with the magnetic power of the Prince of Wales, the charity's president, has won through. The organisation today has a membership of 700 mainly large companies, including 78 of the FTSE-100.\par \par \uc2 As the world's longest-established organisation dedicated to socially responsible business, it has been a model across Europe. In the Netherlands, for example, Samenleving en Bedrijf (Community and Business) was established after business leaders visited the UK charity. BITC's awards for excellence, highlighting best practice, are being adopted in France, Germany and Spain.\par \par \uc2 Distinguishing itself from the US, with its emphasis on hands-off donations, BITC has spent the past decade arguing that throwing cash at community groups means little if a company treats its employees unfairly, pollutes the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  or fails to understand its ethnic minority customers.\par \par \uc2 The organisation is using its 20th anniversary to evaluate what it has learnt and consider future challenges. It is time for tough questions. Has it fundamentally changed business behaviour? What should its future role be?\par \par \uc2 Public attitudes to business have hardened. Mori polls show that 58 per cent of people think company profits are too high, up from about 45 per cent 20 years ago. Nearly 70 per cent think business does not pay enough attention to social responsibility. Only just over a third are aware of business supporting their local community. Why has the message not got through?\par \par \uc2 Ms Cleverdon responds that public scepticism about all institutions has mushroomed, along with transparency and expectations of corporate behaviour. "Part of our challenge has been getting ... the good news out, against a rising tide of expectations and criticism of companies," she says. "You could argue that the image of business would be even worse without us."\par \par \uc2 Business is also under attack for being mean. The corporate sector gave less to charity last year than it did in 1991, according to the National Council for Voluntary Organisations. By and large, the same few companies give the most each year in donations and community contributions, according to the Directory of Social Change, which provides information and training to the voluntary sector.\par \par \uc2 Community involvement is as important as cash, says Ms Cleverdon. But of BITC's 700 members, just 200 have completed its "PerCent Club" index, detailing how much of their pre-tax profits has been donated in cash, time and services. Of these, only 100 have reached the 1 per cent target. "We've not been fierce enough about this," she says.\par \par \uc2 BITC has to wrestle not only with those few company chiefs unmoved by its "Seeing is Believing" visits, such as the one in Bristol, but also with laggards in its own membership.\par \par \uc2 Even when chief executives are willingly converted, it has proved harder to persuade middle managers of the arguments, a problem she believes could be solved by providing more practical advice.\par \par \uc2 However, she strongly defends the idea of an organisation that simultaneously represents and tries to change business. "I'd rather have them in membership so that we can influence them than put tremendous bars to entry, which means you'll only get the good ones in anyhow."\par \par \uc2 In the past five years, the organisation has stepped up pressure on members to measure their performance and demonstrate improvements. Progress has been patchy. More than 180 companies completed last year's index measuring environmental performance, including most FTSE 100 companies. However, only 54 companies reported on the issue of racial diversity, a figure that demonstrates poor understanding of the importance of ethnic minorities as employees or customers.\par \par \uc2 In future, Ms Cleverdon says, reporting on issues such as race and gender may have to be a condition of membership. That would certainly strengthen BITC's own reputation.\par \par \uc2 In a commentary on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the charity's 20th anniversary, Richard Lambert, former FT editor, says there may be a case for doing more to measure the costs and benefits to businesses. "The clearer the business case, the easier it is to justify," he says.\par \par \uc2 To this end, 20 leading BITC companies are piloting reports on a public website, to go live next year, that will provide a basis for comparing how they deal with employees, customers, the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the community and human rights.\par \par \uc2 It is easier to measure inputs - the number of employee volunteering schemes or the amount of time being put into community projects - than outcomes. Volunteers who listen to children reading probably help revitalise failing schools but other factors are likely to be involved. Even inside companies, it is difficult to say for certain that employees remain loyal because of good equal opportunities policies, although these almost certainly contribute to retention.\par \par \uc2 Ms Cleverdon nevertheless argues that BITC's awards for excellence demonstrate measurable and replicable effects on the community. "These things are rigorously reviewed and measured. This is not froth. This is real."\par \par \uc2 Sometimes, there is even a ripple effect far beyond the immediate community. "BG trained 50 prisoners in Reading jail to be lift truck drivers. The normal reoffending rate is about 80 per cent but a year later the rate was only 10 per cent among this group. That has caused the Prison Service to change the way it has been working with employers."\par \par \uc2 However, there is a danger that measurement will be taken to extremes, especially given the intense interest of the government and the European Commission in \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , she argues. Having castigated some of her members for not measuring enough, she warns that external bureaucrats could measure business involvement "out of existence". Preventing this will be part of BITC's job in the future.\par \par \uc2 Within companies, too, enthusiasm for CSR risks undermining ethical behaviour, she says. By giving someone the title of CSR director and treating the issue as a separate function, companies risk removing it from their core business practices.\par \par \uc2 "Everybody says: We don't need to worry about whether our suppliers were or were not employing child labour - that's the responsibility of the CSR department. It isn't. It's the responsibility of everybody who runs the business." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 eecz : \uc2 European Union Countries | eurz : \uc2 Europe | uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pard \ql \li0\r