ll \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 INSIDE TRACK - Crazes that capture the office - SOCIAL EPIDEMICS - The workplace is an ideal \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  for 'viral' ideas. But there can be problems, writes Stephen Overell.\par \par \uc2 Social epidemics never really caught on. In 2000 their future looked assured. One of the publishing sensations of the millennium was The Tipping Point,a best-selling book by Malcolm Gladwell, a journalist with The New Yorker, which aimed to show how ideas, products, messages and behaviour spread just as viruses do.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The term "tipping point" refers to the moment of critical mass, the threshold, the boiling point. The right word at the right time in the right "socially promiscuous" ear can change the world, Mr Gladwell purred. "Look at the world around you. It may seem like an immovable, implacable place. It is not. With the slightest push - in just the right place - it can be tipped."\par \par \uc2 The Tipping Point illustrated this itself during 2000: even President Bill Clinton referred to it in a White House press conference. Since then, social contagions and viral marketing seem to have faded with the decline in the dotcom sector.\par \par \uc2 There is one notable exception: the workplace. This is "ideally suited to the spread of epidemics," says Paul Marsden, a research fellow at the University of Sussex, who also runs Brand Genetics, a consultancy. "You have people densely packed together so ideas proliferate ... very quickly. Things suddenly catch on and become part of the script." Hence management fads, he suggests.\par \par \uc2 But the modern working \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  also generates "mass psychogenic illnesses" such as repetitive strain injury, executive burn-out and stress; the labels feed the symptoms. And it also means work suffers a constantly fluctuating currency of new issues: work/life balance, \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , bullying at work, desk rage, customer delight and so on. "Contagions breed in situations where you have stress, in-security and confusion," says Mr Marsden.\par \par \uc2 This could be because one of the biggest growth industries of the past few years has been the number of professional experts and commentators who pontificate about business and work. They have an interest in selling anxieties, for which they can provide remedies.\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, Jim Carroll, deputy chairman of Bartle, Bogle, Hegarty, the advertising agency, argues that it remains intriguing why work should be more susceptible to "viral ideas" than other parts of life. "Workplace networks tend to accelerate the transmission of ideas," he says. "It is amazing how connected people are - especially with so many e-mail lists - and that maybe makes ideas take hold more easily."\par \par \uc2 He suggests that the connectivity associated with work is now one of the principal sources of social life. "You do see this competitive conversational culture at work - people name-check certain ideas and they become linguistic habits. 'Bricks and clicks', for instance," he says.\par \par \uc2 Among management fads, business process re-engineering (BPR) is the most famous example. Precisely why one of the biggest fads of the 1990s caught on as it did has been the subject of several dense books. Given the post-recessionary mood of the early 1990s, re-engineering had a kind of macho appeal. But that does not explain the phenomenon. Re-engineering the Corporation by James Champy, the movement's manifesto, sold 250,000 copies in its first three months. By 1994, 68 per cent of British companies were re-engineering.\par \par \uc2 Professor If Price at Sheffield Hallam University is an exponent of "meme theory" (how ideas and prac tices spread). He argues that "epidemic" is truly the right word.\par \par \uc2 "For the pioneers, re-engineering was highly successful - but as the idea replicated, it became more virulent and less beneficial as it went on," he says.\par \par \uc2 In Mr Gladwell's book, successful social epidemics such as BPR arise jointly from the infectious agent itself, people and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 First, the message has to be "sticky". Stickiness is a certain quality of memorability; the hamburger chain Wendy's 1984 slogan "Where's the Beef?" is a good example. Then, to infect its way into a cultural mood, it needs a helping hand from "mavens" (pundits, information brokers), "connectors" (people who know people) and "salesmen" (persuaders). Last, the context in which the message is sown needs to be fertile. Human nature should do the rest. No one likes being in a minority of dupes; everyone wants to be in the cultural ascendancy.\par \par \uc2 If it were that simple, the world of work would be awash with successfully manipulated messages. As it is, most workplace issues are wisely ignored. Violence at work, fun at work, the learning organisation, survivor sickness, creativity: all fringe issues that fizzled quickly. Meanwhile, other messages catch on quickly but are then dismissed as bearing no relationship to the facts. "People are our greatest asset" is often seen as a meaningless slogan.\par \par \uc2 However, it would be a foolish business that sought to immunise itself from new ideas by blaming greedy consultants with an axe to grind or gullible media playing up bizarre tittle-tattle.\par \par \uc2 Using the word "epidemic" for any issue that mirrors the behaviour of diseases carries the risk of trivialising serious debates. No idea is ever manufactured out of nothing. The steady growth in the importance of age discrimination, for instance, reflects demographic change, which more and more organisations are choosing to highlight.\par \par \uc2 Mark Goyder, director of the Centre for Tomorrow's Company, the business think-tank, says that organisations such as his need real knowledge of how peer groups think in order to spread certain messages. "Most of us do have a visceral need to be riding along - or at least aware of - the latest wave of concern. Yet there is no controlling events. We have been campaigning for years about the need for transparency in business. Then Enron happens. Everyone is now talking about 'Enronitis' but I suspect it may all look like hysteria in a little while."\par \par \uc2 The fact that these viral crazes that take hold of taste and fashion are so hard to "interrupt" deliberately is one of the lessons of another briefly hip book of 2000. Seth Godin, a former marketing vice-president of Yahoo, argued in Unleashing the Ideavirus that corporations must ride with fads and try to tweak them here and there, rather than just make new products and hope they have some appeal.\par \par \uc2 But there are pointers to whether issues take off or not, others suggest. Charles Sutton, director of business psychologists Nicholson McBride, says workplace ideas tend to crystallise in the public mind when there is a deep overlap of interest between individuals and corporations. Work/ life balance is a good example.\par \par \uc2 Whether or not it is possible to predict whether certain ideas will become crazes, Mr Marsden at Brand Genetics argues that the set-up of workplaces means there will be no let-up in future contagions. People working in close proximity, who are bored or seeking a distraction from pressure, modify and spread ideas for entertainment as much as to be part of any in-crowd.\par \par \uc2 The design of the modern office may even help social epidemics to take hold. Professor Bill Hillier of the Space Syntax Laboratory at the University of London says that cutting-edge office design is aimed at using movement through a workspace to encourage innovation. "The idea is to get people who would not normally talk to each other to do so and so spark new concepts. You don't want work-groups all facing each other - it is across-group communication, rather than in-group communication, that is important."\par \par \uc2 Might this help social epidemics, too? "I don't know about spreading contagious ideas," Prof Hillier says. "I am not aware of any work on it." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gjob : \uc2 Labor Issues\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx7