aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 From Dr Henry I. Miller.\par \par \uc2 Sir, Monsanto's self-flagellation ("How Monsanto got bruised in a food fight", March 8) is misplaced. It is, indeed, to blame for many of the problems that confront genetically modified crops, but not in the way it portrays it.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The fundamental mistake by Monsanto (and a handful of other leading agribusiness companies) was to insist that, because of their intrinsic uniqueness, genetically modified plants and the foods derived from them merit extraordinary government oversight. Using regulation as a market entry barrier to smaller competitors, the companies requested more restrictive regulation than could be justified on scientific grounds. Not only did the resulting policies make research and development hugely and unnecessarily expensive but they also played into activists' scare scenarios, discouraging public acceptance of the new products.\par \par \uc2 Although efforts should be made to reassure the public that GM techniques are in fact safer than more traditional methods of genetic modification, excessive regulation is not the way to do so. As the president of a US national consumer organisation testified to a federal investigative panel: "For obvious reasons, the consumer views the technologies that are most regulated to be the least safe ones. Heavy involvement by government, no matter how well intended, inevitably sends the wrong signals. Rather than ensuring confidence, it raises suspicion and doubt." (Emphasis in original.)\par \par \uc2 The companies appear not to have learned the Rule of Holes: When you're in a hole, stop digging. Hendrik A. Verfaillie, Monsanto's chief executive, "believes the way forward is for Monsanto to attempt to find common ground with its critics rather than confront them". That policy didn't work for Neville Chamberlain, and it won't work for Monsanto.\par \par \uc2 Henry I. Miller, The Hoover Institution, Stanford University, Stanford, CA 94305, US\par \par \uc2 From Prof Ernst von Weizsacker.\par \par \uc2 Sir, I welcome your series on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Your article on Monsanto, however, is deficient. It suggests that Europeans are basically irrational consumers and that Monsanto made no other mistake than underestimating that irrationality.\par \par \uc2 I said to Kate Fish, Monsanto's vice-president for public policy, long ago that health effects of genetically engineered food are not the only issue. Greenpeace, Third World Network and other critics typically name three entirely different issues they find annoying about Monsanto: first, the mounting evidence of ecological risks of GM crops; second, the threat to farmers in developing countries and their farmers rights by Monsanto's aggressive policy on seed patenting; third, the "revolving door" between Monsanto staff and the US regulatory authorities with its inherent conflict of interest.\par \par \uc2 Your readers and Monsanto should not be surprised if the company's credibility remains low outside the US.\par \par \uc2 Ernst von Weizsacker, Founding President, Wuppertal Institute for Climate, \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Energy, 53061 Bonn, Germany. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 monsan : \uc2 Monsanto Co\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i25 : \uc2 Chemicals | i2569 : \uc2 Biotechnology | igmfd : \uc2 Genetically Modified Food | i01001 : \uc2 Agriculture | i0 : \uc2 Agriculture/Forestry | i2568 : \uc2 Pesticides | i41 : \uc2 Food/Beverages/Tobacco | iagro : \uc2 Agrochemicals | ifood : \uc2 Food Products\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nlet : \uc2 Letter | nrgn : \uc2 R