\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2002 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Business sponsorship of the arts has dropped sharply after years of steady growth, according to a survey published yesterday.\par \par \uc2 Corporate expenditure on the arts dropped in 2000-01 to \u163\'00\'A3114.4m, after reaching a record \u163\'00\'A3150.4m in 1999-2000.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Colin Tweedy, chief executive of Arts &Business, which promotes arts sponsorship, said he feared that "companies may see helping the arts as old-fashioned. They are taking \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  more seriously than ever before but more money is going into inner-city regeneration, social exclusion, education and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ".\par \par \uc2 Most of the decline was accounted for by the reduction in corporate help for capital projects. With many lottery-backed arts buildings - such as the Royal Opera House in Covent Garden, central London, and Tate Modern in south London - now up and running, business help for new developments fell from \u163\'00\'A345.7m to just \u163\'00\'A39m.\par \par \uc2 However, general business sponsorship also declined, from \u163\'00\'A359.6m to \u163\'00\'A357.6m. Many big supporters, such as BT, Lloyds, NatWest, Shell and Prudential, which in the past often spent more than \u163\'00\'A31m a year backing the arts, have reduced their investment.\par \par \uc2 The figures predate the fallout from September 11 and the fears of recession, which both affected business dona tions late in 2001. Asa result, the situation has probably deteriorated even more over the past six months.\par \par \uc2 David Gordon, chief executive of the Royal Academy, which is struggling to find a big backer for an important show of Aztec art in the autumn, said: "It is more difficult now. The major investment houses, which used exhibitions to entertain thousands of guests are having a bad time, and companies are keener on social responsibility, which rarely includes the arts, a dreadful mistake. The media too has cut back on its support."\par \par \uc2 The Royal Academy receives no government aid and relies on sponsorship for around \u163\'00\'A31m a year, out of a turnover of \u163\'00\'A320m.\par \par \uc2 The Royal Shakespeare Company is also having difficulties finding a successor to its main sponsor, Allied Domecq, which had contributed around \u163\'00\'A31.1m a year for many years. It said: "We hope to fix a deal within the next six weeks, but in the meantime we are forging successful partnerships on individual projects.\par \par \uc2 "ATOS, the IT firm, is backing our new Much Ado and Antony &Cleopatra with \u163\'00\'A3120,000, but more to the point it is helping us find IT solutions to our customer relations problems. In addition, Pearson has given us \u163\'00\'A325,000 towards our visit to China next month because it is interested in developing English language programmes there."\par \par \uc2 Colin Mackenzie, head of development at the National Gallery, said: "We could not find a sponsor for our next show, on fabrics in art, but now the members are backing it." However, he is optimistic: "We were worried about losing corporate members, who contribute \u163\'00\'A3500,000 between them, but we have only lost one out of 28."\par \par \uc2 Arts &Business has switched its emphasis from seeking large cheques to underwrite expensive opera productions to integrating the arts into corporate life.\par \par \uc2 Sponsorship in kind rose from \u163\'00\'A311.3m to \u163\'00\'A318.1m in 2000-01. Typical was BMW's help for Creation Theatre Company, which enabled it to perform inside BMW showrooms, and Oracle, the computer services company, which devised a computer access programme for Polka Theatre.\par \par \uc2 Among the individual art forms, museums and galleries, with their opportunities for entertaining corporate guests, remain the most popular with sponsors, attracting \u163\'00\'A325.2m in 2000-01.\par \par \uc2 London Edition 2. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gent : \uc2 Arts/Entertainment\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctl