clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Financial Times (FT.Com)\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FTCOM\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2002 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Executives charged with their companies' social responsibility programmes are busy attending the many conferences springing up on the subject. But when it comes to exchanging business cards at such events, an interesting phenomenon emerges. For these executives possess a curious range of titles - from PR manager to vice-president of philanthropy or director of public affairs. The diversity provides an indication of the problems companies are having in integrating \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  into the workforce. Should there be a separate department to deal with it, or should its principles be brought to bear on every aspect of the business?\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The first option certainly looks easiest. But CSR is like honesty, argues Elliot Schrage, former senior vice-president of global affairs at Gap, who now teaches at Columbia Business School. "You shouldn't be saying, 'we have a department of honesty'. And you shouldn't have a department of corporate responsibility. Everyone should be thinking about how their operations impact on the community."\par \par \uc2 Part of the problem lies in the fact that CSR remains poorly defined. In the US, for example, it is still sometimes deemed part of a corporation's philanthropic activities. At the same time, the current focus on transparency, corporate governance and responsible behaviour has propelled CSR from a quiet corner of the corporate world to centre stage - and human resources are struggling to catch up.\par \par \uc2 "What's tended to happen," says Alyson Warhurst, director of the corporate citizenship unit at the University of Warwick, "is that people have come in as, say, engineers and taken on responsibility for health and safety and perhaps had \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  added on. Then that may have expanded to include social responsibility.\par \par \uc2 "That's where they have real difficulties because they're now reporting to senior managers who have more communications skills and better grounding in governance and international issues - so there is this potential for tension."\par \par \uc2 People can be recruited with specific knowledge in human rights or environmental management but no supply of CSR candidates exists from which companies can put together a team.\par \par \uc2 While business schools are beginning to catch on to the idea, the integration of CSR into MBA programmes varies widely from school to school. In many cases, volunteer activities remain the main teaching vehicle, while environmental subjects are often separate modules or elective courses.\par \par \uc2 So where do companies find talent in this area? Three models are emerging: bringing in people from outside; training people within the business; and establishing partnerships with local bodies, aid agencies and lobby groups.\par \par \uc2 How companies build their CSR workforce also depends on what they do. For those handling supply chain issues, having staff with knowledge of human and labour rights is crucial.\par \par \uc2 The Gap model, says Mr Schrage, was to start building the expertise from within. Gap deployed more than 80 people around the world whose sole responsibility was factories' compliance with ethical sourcing criteria. Then Mr Schrage was brought in for his experience in building partnerships with local groups. "They realised there were limits to what they could do by building capacity internally," he says.\par \par \uc2 In recent years Nike, facing similar issues, has quadrupled the number of employees dealing with labour practices. Maria Eitel, its vice-president for corporate responsibility, admits this has been tough. "Frankly we can only hire people so fast in this area because of the issue around training," she says.\par \par \uc2 The third model - partnerships - is strongly advocated by many. When it comes to human rights issues, says Arvin Ganesan, director of the business and human rights programme at the Washington, DC-based Human Rights Watch, there should be consultation.\par \par \uc2 "Those are issues you want to ingrain into the culture of the company," he says. "But it's a bit different when you're talking about community development projects. Then you need to get a development expert."\par \par \uc2 Even here companies have to tread carefully, since lobby groups may be reluctant to serve as consultants for business. Lobby groups' agendas can be at odds with the goals of the corporate world.\par \par \uc2 "It would be wrong to try to incorporate non-government organisations as part of the company," says Lord Browne, chief executive of BP. "But they do have a lot of experience, some of them."\par \par \uc2 Prof Warhurst points to another potential resource: academia. "Partnerships are the way to go but I think universities are missing the opportunity to be one of those partners. There's a level of research expertise that academia could bring to this picture - and they aren't doing that now."\par \par \uc2 That expertise is becoming a valuable commodity as companies whose focus was making garments or drilling for oil are having to delve into areas such as rural education or healthcare programmes. But although building a workforce able to manage the challenges of CSR may be tough, the potential pitfalls of failing to do so are legion. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 eecz : \uc2 European Union Countries | eurz : \uc2 Europe | uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IPC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Education &Training | General News | Government 