a\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Peter Woicke, head of the International Finance Corporation, the World Bank's private sector lending arm, recalls with relish a conversation he had with an oil company manager in Kazakhstan. Mr Woicke challenged him on the social and environmental impact of the company's operations.\par \par \uc2 "After five minutes, the manager said: 'Mr Woicke, this is rubbish. I was sent here to get the oil out of the ground as quickly as possible. Don't tell me I have to build kindergartens and schools and roads.' Then we had a two-or-three-hour discussion and he said: 'I want to talk more to you.' He recognised that it would not help him if he was doing this in a hostile \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Corporate citizenship, or sustainability, as the IFC describes it, is sometimes seen as a luxury that only wealthy western multi-nationals can afford. This is a damaging myth, says Mr Woicke, a former senior banker with JP Morgan who has been executive vice-president of the IFC since 1999. He argues that the business case for sustain-ability is even stronger for companies in developing countries.\par \par \uc2 "In the developed world, the tax system, regulation and self-regulation take care of environmental issues. But in the poor countries you have little regulation [and] little oversight from governments, and therefore companies have to pay attention to these things themselves."\par \par \uc2 Public opinion in emerging markets is increasingly aware of social and environmental issues, he says. "In our age of information availability, the consumer, even in countries like China and Russia, is demanding better behaviour of companies."\par \par \uc2 In the run-up to the United Nations world summit on sustainable development in Johannesburg in August, the IFC is calling for a greater role for the private sector, to complement that of governments. Next month it will publish what it describes as a ground-breaking study* of the benefits to companies in developing countries of adopting higher social, environmental and governance standards. The IFC has collaborated on this study with SustainAbility, a consultancy and think-tank with offices in London and New York, and Ethos, a Brazilian institute specialising in \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The report examines the experiences of 176 companies of all sizes, in 60 countries, and finds that sustainable practices can be linked with lower costs, higher revenues, reduced risk, better reputation and staff morale, and greater access to capital.\par \par \uc2 Improvements in corporate governance and management systems at Bank of Shanghai, for example, helped it to attract investment from HSBC and other foreign banks. Before financing from the IFC, and the appointment as a director of John Langlois, a former managing director of JP Morgan, the board did little more than approve annual business plans and dividend payments, the study says.\par \par \uc2 Audit, compensation and risk management committees have been set up. Strategy has shifted from a focus on dividend payments to increasing retained earnings in order to strengthen capital adequacy. Some employees have resisted the new transparency of the bank's operations; more training is needed. But staff motivation has generally increased.\par \par \uc2 Another example is that of Cembrit, a small building materials company in the Czech Republic. Cembrit has expanded rapidly through exports to the European Union after an IFC-backed investment of $15m (GBP10m), which included switching from asbestos-based production to an environmentally sound cellulose-based process. Without the modernisation, Cembrit would have been forced to close. Daniel Bubla, managing director, says: "The purpose of the exercise was to get ahead of competition and conquer new markets."\par \par \uc2 Working in a healthier \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  has boosted staff morale and productivity and the company's expansion has benefited the local economy. Further improvements include stopping the discharge of untreated effluent into the Berounka river.\par \par \uc2 The research finds that a reduction in costs is the most common result of sustainable practices for companies in emerging markets, regardless of size. Multi-nationals based in developed countries experience less tangible benefits, such as a reduction in risk and greater employee skills.\par \par \uc2 The report stresses that sustainability is not a magic recipe for success; companies need the support of governments as well as pressure from investors and consumers.\par \par \uc2 Publicising its success in raising standards is important to the IFC, which has come under fire from campaigners for backing projects such as the Chad-Cameroon oil pipeline. Mr Woicke says he does not mind the IFC acting as a shield for multinationals "as long as we can prove that we're really adding value to these projects".\par \par \uc2 Are the required investments not beyond the reach of some businesses in developing countries as they grapple with fundamental problems such as political unrest, corruption, poor infrastructure, or a workforce devastated by Aids? The study says more research is needed into the circumstances in which sustainability initiatives fail. "Where we're still struggling is with small companies," says Mr Woicke.\par \par \uc2 Yet he dismisses the argument that imposing these standards amounts to a trade barrier. "A good entrepreneur in Africa or Brazil or China or India wants to compete with entrepreneurs in Germany or the US. I think we're underestimating their intelligence and their ambition if we say: 'They don't want to have the standards we have.' It's an extremely colonial attitude."\par \par \uc2 That said, the companies he cites took some persuading that the investment would be worth it. He remembers asking Luiz Fernando Furlan, chairman of Sadia, a Brazilian food processing business that has extensively upgraded its health and safety practices, what he thought of the standards imposed as a condition for IFC financing.\par \par \uc2 "He said: 'You know, Peter, I hated them - until we got the award for the most environmentally conscious company in Brazil. I'm now totally on your side because it has helped my marketing.' "\par \par \uc2 Rafael Wong, executive vice-president of Reybancorp in Ecuador, says: "When we first obtained financing from IFC, the environmental standards seemed like an obstacle. But we now realise that they have helped to build a strong business. In five years, there will be no access to international markets for companies that do not show respect for the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ."\par \par \uc2 *Developing Value, the Business Case for Sustainability in Emerging Markets. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.sustainability.com/store"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.sustainability.com/store}}}\uc2  or {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.worldbank.org/publications"}}{\fldrslt{\cf