a\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  A black pall of deep despair has settled over the good people who put out Business Ethics, one of the world's thinnest magazines. \par \par \uc2  Just as the staff was preparing to publish the gala 15th-anniversary issue -- the combined May/June and July/August editions, which fills 20 pages, not counting the cover -- the robber barons of American capitalism spoiled their party by proving (once again) that the title of the magazine just might be an oxymoron. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  Business Ethics is a magazine devoted to a movement that crusades for what it calls CSR, which stands for "\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 ." This movement tries to persuade corporations to be have decently toward their employees, stockholders, communities and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Apparently the magazine's editors thought the movement was doing just fine until they got wind of the nefarious doings at Enron, WorldCom, Tyco, Adelphia, Arthur Andersen and other rapacious corporations. \par \par \uc2  Now, the folks at Business Ethics are in a sad state of hand-wringing, soul-searching and existential angst. The general tone is summed up in the headline and subhead of a column by contributing writer Milton Moskowitz: "What Has CSR Really Accomplished? Much of the movement has been a public relations smoke screen." \par \par \uc2  "It appears that much of the \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  movement has dealt in peripheral matters, in language, in mechanical social screens. Behind the scenes, the dirty work went on as usual," writes Moskowitz, who is the co-author of Fortune magazine's annual list of "The 100 Best Companies to Work for in America." "I am sorry to be so cynical. But you have to admit it's depressing." \par \par \uc2  Equally cynical and depressed is the editor of Business Ethics, Marjorie Kelly. "The lesson," Kelly writes, "is that all the things CSR has been measuring and fighting for and applauding may be colossally beside the point." \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  movement considered Enron a great company, she writes: "It won a spot for three years on the list of the 100 Best Companies to Work for. .  .  . It had great policies on climate change, human rights and (yes indeed) anti-corruption. Its CEO gave speeches at ethics conferences." \par \par \uc2  Now, Kelly says, she's discovered the problem: In the capitalist system, the quest for ever-larger profits tends to trump the ideals of social responsibility. "The system is designed that way," she writes. "It is designed to serve certain people and not others." And those "certain people" are, she adds, "the financial elite." \par \par \uc2  Well, one is tempted to respond with a rousing chorus of "Duh!" \par \par \uc2  The idea that corporations will  shaft  workers, shareholders and Mother Nature in pursuit of the almighty dollar should be obvious to anyone who has ever glanced at an American history textbook. And the fact that corporate executives might utter pious platitudes about ethics while stealing like gangsters would surprise no one familiar with the tale of Richard Whitney, the president of the New York Stock Exchange, who delivered a famous speech titled "Business Honesty" shortly before he was sent to Sing Sing for theft in 1938. \par \par \uc2  But it's not nice to gloat over the naivete of disillusioned idealists. The folks at Business Ethics are not all that different from the rest of us. In the last several decades, politicians, think tanks and the media have convinced the American public that corporations are warm, fuzzy creatures, that CEOs are American heroes and that government regulation of business is meddlesome and unnecessary. Now we know -- or ought to know -- that it was a lot of baloney. \par \par \uc2  Kelly ends her essay with an italicized notice: "Business Ethics is laying plans to convert itself into a nonprofit to be called the Economic Democracy Project and is seeking allies." \par \par \uc2  Let's hope this new movement is less naive and more effective than the old one. \par \par \uc2  Making Delaware Pay a Toll \par \par \uc2  Some people hate New York. Some people hate California. Some people hate Texas. The state that Jonathan Chiat hates is .  .  . Delaware. \par \par \uc2  Instead of "The First State," says Chiat's essay in the New Republic, Delaware ought to be known as "the worst state." \par \par \uc2  Chiat's loathing began several years ago when he first drove through Delaware on  Interstate 95 and ended up in a two-hour traffic jam. At first he thought the jam was caused by some horrific accident. It wasn't. It was just the standard traffic jam caused by the tollbooths that Delaware uses to extract $2 for the dubious privilege of enduring the 11 miles of stop-and-go traffic on its turnpike. \par \par \uc2  Most of us just grumble and curse about Delaware's annoying tolls. Not Chiat. He delved into the history of Delaware and concluded that "it is a rapacious parasite state with a long history of disloyalty and avarice." \par \par \uc2  In the early days of our republic, Delaware barred black folks -- slave or free -- from "even entering a county seat on Election Day." It was "the last Union state to ban slavery." It was "the last state to ban public whipping" -- flogging convicts until 1952. \par \par \uc2  But that's just the background. Today, Chiat writes, "Delaware's greatest specialty is finding ways to siphon money out of non-residents." \par \par \uc2  Those wretched tolls are one method of siphoning. More important is Delaware's role as an accomplice to the kind of corporate practices that give the folks at Business Ethics the heebie-jeebies. \par \par \uc2  Ever wonder why so many credit card companies are located in Delaware? It's because Delaware permits the companies to gouge borrowers for more interest than other states do. \par \par \uc2  Ever wonder why so many companies are incorporated in Delaware? It's because, as Chiat writes, "corporations based there are held to the laxest possible standards of disclosure, shareholder rights and fiduciary responsibility." \par \par \uc2  Chiat's wonderfully vicious screed convinced me that Delaware is exactly what the title of the piece calls it -- a "Rogue State." In fact, Delaware's nasty triumvirate of tollbooths, credit card shylocks and sleazy corporations constitutes an "axis of evil" that presents at least as much of a threat to the typical American as Iraq. \par \par \uc2  I say we invade the place. Send in the Marines! Let them clear out this nest of thieves. It won't take long. The whole operation will be over quicker than the typical speech by Delaware's senior senator, the logorrheic Joe Biden. \par \par \uc2  Do it now. The time is right. The all-important coastal towns of Bethany and Rehoboth are already occupied by towel-wearing out-of-staters, which will prevent the arrival of arms shipments from North Korea or Iran. If we hurry, we can tear down those damn tollbooths before the Labor Day weekend. \par \par \uc2  Come on, America, forward march! \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CT\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  http://www.washingtonpost.com \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 advcos : \uc2 MCI Inc | intnth : \uc2 Enron Creditors Recovery Corp.\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i1 : \uc2 Energy | i16 : \uc2 Electricity/Gas Utilities | i7902 : \uc2 Telecommunications\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} 